(4706, 2815, '_wp_attachment_metadata', 'a:5:{s:5:"width";i:1260;s:6:"height";i:900;s:4:"file";s:40:"2013/12/Profil-bloggeur_Ndiaga-Seck1.jpg";s:5:"sizes";a:3:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:40:"Profil-bloggeur_Ndiaga-Seck1-150x150.jpg";s:5:"width";i:150;s:6:"height";i:150;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:6:"medium";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:40:"Profil-bloggeur_Ndiaga-Seck1-300x214.jpg";s:5:"width";i:300;s:6:"height";i:214;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:5:"large";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:41:"Profil-bloggeur_Ndiaga-Seck1-1024x731.jpg";s:5:"width";i:1024;s:6:"height";i:731;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:10:"image_meta";a:10:{s:8:"aperture";i:0;s:6:"credit";s:12:"Brett Morton";s:6:"camera";s:0:"";s:7:"caption";s:1690:"Sotraki Temporary Site, Goma… 8th CEPAC, a local NGO operating in Goma distributes BP-5 buscuits and Plumpy nut to malnourished children living in the Sotraki site… Following months of relative peace after the takeover of Goma by the M23 rebels in November, 2012, fighting once again broke out on the edge of Goma between the M23 and the Congolese Army (FARDC) in May, 2013. Upwards of 6,000 people fled their homes towards the city center, where they sought shelter in schools, churches, or with host families.\n\nIn response to the displacement the humanitarian community mobilized resources to create numerous temporary sites to cater to the displaced. UNICEF coordinated with partners Norwegian  Refugee Council (NRC) and Norwegian Church Aid (NCA) to provide shelter and Water, Sanitation and Hygiene as well as logistical support to the management of the sites. \n\nWith more than 1,700 families staying at the Sotraki site (as of 04 June, 2013) UNICEF partner NCA responded within one week of the displacement to construct 16 latrines,12 showers, and instal a 30m3 water bladder which provides a constant flow to 12 taps in the site. In addition, NCA hygiene teams have organized and supervised the regular cleaning of the latrines, as well as spreading general hygiene messages.\nNRC has contributed to the establishment of numerous tents in which to hose the displaced in both the Sotraki and Buhimba sites. In addition, through UNICEF RRMP funds, NRC has provided transportation of displaced to the Buhimba site in an effort to decongest the Sotraki site. \nPlans are underway for an NFI distribution to be carried out through UNICEF RRMP partners NRC and Slidarités International.";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1370003464;s:9:"copyright";s:24:"©UNICEF DRC/2013/Morton";s:12:"focal_length";i:0;s:3:"iso";i:0;s:13:"shutter_speed";i:0;s:5:"title";s:0:"";}}'),
(4707, 2817, '_wp_attached_file', '2013/12/Profil-bloggeur_Sylvie-Fouet21.jpg'),
(4708, 2817, '_wp_attachment_metadata', 'a:5:{s:5:"width";i:647;s:6:"height";i:462;s:4:"file";s:42:"2013/12/Profil-bloggeur_Sylvie-Fouet21.jpg";s:5:"sizes";a:2:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:42:"Profil-bloggeur_Sylvie-Fouet21-150x150.jpg";s:5:"width";i:150;s:6:"height";i:150;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:6:"medium";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:42:"Profil-bloggeur_Sylvie-Fouet21-300x214.jpg";s:5:"width";i:300;s:6:"height";i:214;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:10:"image_meta";a:10:{s:8:"aperture";i:0;s:6:"credit";s:12:"Brett Morton";s:6:"camera";s:0:"";s:7:"caption";s:2112:"UNICEF Deputy Representative Sylvie Fouet visits PEAR+ (Programme Elargi d’Assistance aux Retours) activities in the Matanda area of South Kivu.\n\nPEAR Plus provides an integrated package of assistance and capacity building to communities; local and state authorities in the sectors of Health, Water, Hygiene and Sanitation, Education and Child Protection.Sectorial specific activities include the following: School reconstruction, support to transparent and equitable structure management, teacher-training, support to parent/teacher associations, provision of education kits and didactic material. Restoration and development of sustainable access to safe water and healthy environment; rehabilitation of health centres, reinforcement of health staff and directors’ capacities; provision of basic medical necessities; support to vaccination campaigns and community-based treatment for malnutrition as well as the identification and strengthening child protection networks and responses are all part of the Programme.  \n\nAccompanied by peacebuilding activities and interventions designed to improve social cohesion, emphasis is put on governance activities (linked to social service provision) and conflict risk reduction in order to keep the Programme relevant to the evolving context and consequent needs. Increased community participation and ownership, as well as a reinforcement of the social contract between community, local and state authorities are increasingly key outputs of PEAR+’s approach.  \n\nA more explicit relationship with UNICEF’s long term programming provides a clear exit strategy and guarantees a degree of sustainability in the medium term, whilst a closer alignment with UNICEF’s emergency response mechanisms and the integration of sectorial emergency preparedness helps improve community resilience to the impact of conflict.  In recognition of the fluid nature in the east, the objective is to develop a way of working which supports social and economic rehabilitation; reinforces community resilience and eases the transition to emergency assistance or longer term support.";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1384425635;s:9:"copyright";s:25:"© UNICEF RDC/2013/Morton";s:12:"focal_length";i:0;s:3:"iso";i:0;s:13:"shutter_speed";i:0;s:5:"title";s:2102:"UNICEF Deputy Representative Sylvie Fouet visits PEAR+ (Programme Elargi d?Assistance aux Retours) activities in the Matanda area of South Kivu.\n\nPEAR Plus provides an integrated package of assistance and capacity building to communities; local and state authorities in the sectors of Health, Water, Hygiene and Sanitation, Education and Child Protection.Sectorial specific activities include the following: School reconstruction, support to transparent and equitable structure management, teacher-training, support to parent/teacher associations, provision of education kits and didactic material. Restoration and development of sustainable access to safe water and healthy environment; rehabilitation of health centres, reinforcement of health staff and directors? capacities; provision of basic medical necessities; support to vaccination campaigns and community-based treatment for malnutrition as well as the identification and strengthening child protection networks and responses are all part of the Programme.  \n\nAccompanied by peacebuilding activities and interventions designed to improve social cohesion, emphasis is put on governance activities (linked to social service provision) and conflict risk reduction in order to keep the Programme relevant to the evolving context and consequent needs. Increased community participation and ownership, as well as a reinforcement of the social contract between community, local and state authorities are increasingly key outputs of PEAR+?s approach.  \n\nA more explicit relationship with UNICEF?s long term programming provides a clear exit strategy and guarantees a degree of sustainability in the medium term, whilst a closer alignment with UNICEF?s emergency response mechanisms and the integration of sectorial emergency preparedness helps improve community resilience to the impact of conflict.  In recognition of the fluid nature in the east, the objective is to develop a way of working which supports social and economic rehabilitation; reinforces community resilience and eases the transition to emergency assistance or longer term support.";}}'),
