(8822, 5017, '_wp_attachment_metadata', 'a:5:{s:5:"width";i:624;s:6:"height";i:499;s:4:"file";s:25:"2014/01/1305311203421.jpg";s:5:"sizes";a:2:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:25:"1305311203421-150x150.jpg";s:5:"width";i:150;s:6:"height";i:150;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}s:6:"medium";a:4:{s:4:"file";s:25:"1305311203421-300x239.jpg";s:5:"width";i:300;s:6:"height";i:239;s:9:"mime-type";s:10:"image/jpeg";}}s:10:"image_meta";a:10:{s:8:"aperture";d:2.7999999999999998;s:6:"credit";s:12:"Brett Morton";s:6:"camera";s:11:"NIKON D800E";s:7:"caption";s:1690:"Sotraki Temporary Site, Goma… 8th CEPAC, a local NGO operating in Goma distributes BP-5 buscuits and Plumpy nut to malnourished children living in the Sotraki site… Following months of relative peace after the takeover of Goma by the M23 rebels in November, 2012, fighting once again broke out on the edge of Goma between the M23 and the Congolese Army (FARDC) in May, 2013. Upwards of 6,000 people fled their homes towards the city center, where they sought shelter in schools, churches, or with host families.\n\nIn response to the displacement the humanitarian community mobilized resources to create numerous temporary sites to cater to the displaced. UNICEF coordinated with partners Norwegian  Refugee Council (NRC) and Norwegian Church Aid (NCA) to provide shelter and Water, Sanitation and Hygiene as well as logistical support to the management of the sites. \n\nWith more than 1,700 families staying at the Sotraki site (as of 04 June, 2013) UNICEF partner NCA responded within one week of the displacement to construct 16 latrines,12 showers, and instal a 30m3 water bladder which provides a constant flow to 12 taps in the site. In addition, NCA hygiene teams have organized and supervised the regular cleaning of the latrines, as well as spreading general hygiene messages.\nNRC has contributed to the establishment of numerous tents in which to hose the displaced in both the Sotraki and Buhimba sites. In addition, through UNICEF RRMP funds, NRC has provided transportation of displaced to the Buhimba site in an effort to decongest the Sotraki site. \nPlans are underway for an NFI distribution to be carried out through UNICEF RRMP partners NRC and Slidarités International.";s:17:"created_timestamp";i:1370001822;s:9:"copyright";s:24:"©UNICEF DRC/2013/Morton";s:12:"focal_length";s:2:"50";s:3:"iso";s:3:"320";s:13:"shutter_speed";s:5:"0.008";s:5:"title";s:1686:"Sotraki Temporary Site, Goma? 8th CEPAC, a local NGO operating in Goma distributes BP-5 buscuits and Plumpy nut to malnourished children living in the Sotraki site? Following months of relative peace after the takeover of Goma by the M23 rebels in November, 2012, fighting once again broke out on the edge of Goma between the M23 and the Congolese Army (FARDC) in May, 2013. Upwards of 6,000 people fled their homes towards the city center, where they sought shelter in schools, churches, or with host families.\n\nIn response to the displacement the humanitarian community mobilized resources to create numerous temporary sites to cater to the displaced. UNICEF coordinated with partners Norwegian  Refugee Council (NRC) and Norwegian Church Aid (NCA) to provide shelter and Water, Sanitation and Hygiene as well as logistical support to the management of the sites. \n\nWith more than 1,700 families staying at the Sotraki site (as of 04 June, 2013) UNICEF partner NCA responded within one week of the displacement to construct 16 latrines,12 showers, and instal a 30m3 water bladder which provides a constant flow to 12 taps in the site. In addition, NCA hygiene teams have organized and supervised the regular cleaning of the latrines, as well as spreading general hygiene messages.\nNRC has contributed to the establishment of numerous tents in which to hose the displaced in both the Sotraki and Buhimba sites. In addition, through UNICEF RRMP funds, NRC has provided transportation of displaced to the Buhimba site in an effort to decongest the Sotraki site. \nPlans are underway for an NFI distribution to be carried out through UNICEF RRMP partners NRC and Slidarités International.";}}'),
