(3337, 1, '2013-12-27 08:58:43', '2013-12-27 08:58:43', 'IRC DRC RRMP WaSH Intervention. 13 March, 2013. - -Mwateganyi, 45, married mother of 4 children – Agnes, 15 – Namwigima, 10 – Faida, 5 – Bulonza, 1 \n-Displaced since January 5th from Maziba (towards Luntukulu) when fighting broke out between RM and FARDC\n-This is the 5th time they’ve been displaced. First time was in ’98. In 2002 it was MaiMai vs. RCD.\n-Staying in the home of Zihalirwa, who has hosted them each of the times they’ve been displaced as he is a family friend.\n-“When we heard the shots we fled fearing for our lives. We had to leave everything behind, and took only the little we could carry immediately.”\n-They left on foot, walking for about one day to cover the 15-20 km.\n-The first difficulty is always the stress of dying. And then the risks along the route. The sickness of the children is a problem also. All the children fell sick by the time we arrived. \n-In Maziba they are farmers.\n-“When we return home we already know everything will be missing or destroyed. The last time they even took the doors of the house.”\n-“Here the big need is to find food. And clothes. And cooking utensils, and jerrycans. And the health of the children is very difficult.”\n-The NFI kit is very important. We can use the sheeting when we return to use as a roof. The husband has already returned to begin rebuilding. The blanked and mat are good to have here and upon return. With the clothes the children can go to church. The pots and pans are so helpful because before we had to wait for others to finish using the pots and pans before we could start cooking. For everything else it was necessary to rely on the kindness of others to give us, but they don’t have much so it is difficult for them to give.\n-The water source is very important. Before we had the latrine all the children had diarrhea. We had to wait for 1-2 hours at the water point to fetch water because of the crowds. Now there are no crowds.\n-Ziahlirwa explains that as a host family it becomes very difficult for him also because they have little to give. \n-This is the first time they have received any aid with the displaced.\n-“Thanks to the displaced I now have a latrine and clean water! I never had a proper latrine before, so it’s very nice.”\n-When asked why he hosts the displaced, ZIahlirwa explained that “ One day I could also be displaced.”', 'NFI Header', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'nfi-header', '', '', '2013-12-27 08:58:43', '2013-12-27 08:58:43', '', 3334, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/NFI-Header1.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
