(2823, 1, '2013-12-10 08:10:02', '2013-12-10 08:10:02', '[one_third]\n<h4><strong>Jonathan</strong></h4>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://ponabana.com/author/jonathan/"><img class="wp-image-3395 aligncenter" alt="Nathan" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Nathan1.jpg" width="557" height="371" /></a>\n<em>Jonathan a 16 ans et il est enfant reporter de Kinshasa. Il étudie au collège Saint Joseph et aimerait devenir avocat pour défendre les droits des enfants. Son rêve? Que son pays "devienne un pays digne des enfants, un pays qui respecte les droits de l''enfant et qui les mettent au centre de tout.</em></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n[/one_third][one_third]\n<h4><strong>Eunice</strong></h4>\n<a href="http://www.kidsareheroes.org/heroes/Eunice-Muba.php"><img class="wp-image-1890 aligncenter" alt="Eunice MUBA," src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Eunice-MUBA-1024x683.jpg" width="375" height="250" /></a>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Eunice a 14 ans et elle est enfant reporter de Kinshasa. Elle a représenté les enfants d''Afrique Centrale devant les leaders Africains au Sommet de l''Union Africaine à Addis Abeba en 2012. Dans son discours, elle a rappelé les droits de l''enfant à la survie, la liberté d''expression, l''éducation, la santé et a appelé à l''élaboration d''une stratégie pour prévenir les conflits armés qui affectent les enfants. Pourquoi enfant reporter? "Parce que je veux faire de mon pays un meilleur endroit où les enfants pourront vivre".</em></p>\n\n<h4>[/one_third][one_third_last]</h4>\n<h4><strong>Samy</strong></h4>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://ponabana.com/author/samy/"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-3214" alt="samy" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/samy1.jpg" width="422" height="281" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Samy a 10 ans et il est en 5è année à l’école primaire Nsango Magulu, à 22 km de la ville de Kalemie. Il fait partie des 40 enfants reporters de la province du Nord Katanga formés en Août 2013. Il réside avec sa famille dans le camps de déplacés de Nsango Magulu, en provenance de Bendera.</em></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><em> </em>[/one_third_last]</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">[separator]</p>\n[one_third]\n<h4> <em> </em><strong style="font-size: 1em;">Rolande</strong></h4>\n<a href="http://ponabana.com/author/rolande/"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Bandundu 4" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Bandundu-4.jpg" width="230" height="197" /></a>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Rolande a 13 ans et elle est enfant reporter à Bandundu. Elle s''engage aux côtés de ses amis pour lutter contre le mariage précoce et l''exploitation économique des enfants. Plus tard, elle sera institutrice pour transmettre ce qu''elle a appris</em></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n[/one_third][one_third]\n<h4><strong> Nathan</strong></h4>\n<h4><strong><a href="http://ponabana.com/author/jonathan/"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Profil Jonathan" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Profil-Jonathan1.jpg" width="373" height="249" /></a></strong></h4>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Nathan a 15 ans et il est au Collège Notre Dame du Congo à Kinshasa. Passionné de football, il joue milieu pour "organiser le jeu". Plus tard, il veut être un avocat reconnu et travailler pour la Cour Pénale Internationale. Sa devise: "Que tous nous soyons un!"</em></p>\n\n<h4>[/one_third][one_third_last]</h4>\n<h4><strong>Bora</strong></h4>\n<h4><a href="http://ponabana.com/author/bora/" target="_blank"><img class=" wp-image-4308 aligncenter" alt="IMG_6748" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/IMG_67482.jpg" width="504" height="336" /></a></h4>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Bora a 14 ans et elle est enfant reporter à Lubumbashi. Plus tard elle veut être criminologue. Aujourd''hui elle s''attache à rassembler les enfants reporters de toutes les provinces pour que leur voix résonne jusqu''au bout du monde!</em></p>\n\n<h4><em>. </em>[/one_third_last]</h4>\n[separator]\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Les articles publiés représentent l’opinion de leurs auteurs et n’engagent pas la responsabilité de l’UNICEF.</strong></p>', 'Enfants Blogueurs', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'bloggers', '', '', '2013-12-10 08:10:02', '2013-12-10 08:10:02', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=2823', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(2925, 1, '2013-12-10 13:03:47', '2013-12-10 13:03:47', '[one_half] <strong>Tout ce qu''il faut savoir sur le travail de l''UNICEF et de ses partenaires en République Démocratique du Congo.</strong>\n\nDans cette section vous trouverez l''ensemble des articles publiés par nos spécialistes, partenaires et invités. Une vision unique et authentique du travail accompli sur le terrain.\n\nPour chaque thème sur lequel l''UNICEF travaille en RDC nous vous proposons un état des lieux, les principaux chiffres clefs, les résultats obtenus et les prochaines étapes.\n\nLes principaux programmes sont également détaillés et une carte vous permettra de découvrir où sont situés les bureau de l''UNICEF sur l''ensemble du territoire de la RDC.\n\n[/one_half]\n\n[one_half_last]\n\n[accordion]\n\n[section title="Nos articles"]<a href="/?cat_ID=126">L''ensemble des articles écrits par nos spécialistes, partenaires et invités. Une vision unique et authentique du travail accompli sur le terrain pour les enfants de la RDC.</a> [/section]\n\n[section title="Nos thèmes"]<a href="/?page_id=2932">Pour chaque thème sur lequel l''UNICEF travaille en RDC, retrouvez un état des lieux, les principaux chiffres clefs et les résultats obtenus. </a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Principaux programmes"]<a href="/?page_id=2940">Une fiche descriptive présentant les éléments à retenir sur chacun des principaux programmes mis en place par l''UNICEF en RDC</a>.[/section]\n\n[section title="Présence sur le terrain"]<a href="/?page_id=2747">Une carte de la RDC présentant les différents bureaux de l''UNICEF sur l''ensemble du territoire.</a> [/section]\n\n[section title="Communiqué de presse"] <a href="/?cat_ID=5">Les derniers communiqués de presse publiés par l''UNICEF en RDC</a>[/section]\n\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Notre Travail', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'notre-travail', '', '', '2013-12-10 13:03:47', '2013-12-10 13:03:47', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=2925', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(2932, 1, '2013-12-10 13:21:23', '2013-12-10 13:21:23', '<p style="text-align: justify;">[one_half] <strong>L''UNICEF en RDC travaille sur 7 "thèmes" prioritaires : Education, Santé, Nutrition, Protection, Eau et assainissement, Urgences et Participation.</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Pour chacun de ces thèmes, nous vous proposons une description générale du thème accompagné des principaux chiffres clefs, enjeux majeurs, principales avancées et des perspectives attendues.</p>\n[/one_half]\n\n[one_half_last]\n\n[accordion]\n\n[section title="Education"]<a href="/?page_id=2403">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à l''éducation en RDC.</a> [/section]\n\n[section title="Santé"]<a href="/?page_id=2204">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à la santé en RDC </a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Nutrition"]<a href="/?page_id=2478">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à la nutrition en RDC</a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Protection"]<a href="/?page_id=2374">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à la protection en RDC  </a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Eau et assainissement"] <a href="/?page_id=2139">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à l''eau et l''assainissement en RDC</a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Urgences"] <a href="/?page_id=2456">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés aux urgences en RDC</a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Participation"] <a href="/?page_id=4232" target="_blank">L''essentiel pour comprendre les enjeux liés à la participation en RDC</a>[/section]\n\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Nos thèmes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nos-themes', '', '', '2013-12-10 13:21:23', '2013-12-10 13:21:23', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=2932', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(2940, 1, '2013-12-10 13:42:37', '2013-12-10 13:42:37', '[one_half] <strong>Des outils innovants et flexibles pour améliorer la situation des enfants de la RDC. </strong>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Dans cette section vous trouverez quelques uns des programmes "emblématiques" de l''action que nous menons avec nos partenaires sur le terrain afin de répondre au mieux aux besoins des enfants de la RDC.</p>\n[/one_half]\n\n[one_half_last]\n\n[accordion]\n\n[section title="Réponse Rapide au Mouvement de Population - RRMP"] <a href="/?page_id=1853">Evaluations rapides des besoins et assistance intégrée aux populations vulnérables affectées par les déplacements, le retour et/ou les catastrophes naturelles.</a> [/section]\n\n[section title="Ecoles et Villages assainis"]<a href="/?page_id=2559">Objectif: Réduire la mortalité infantile et la propagation des maladies d''origine hydriques, ainsi qu’un accès à l’eau potable favorisé dans les zones rurales et périurbaines</a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Enfants Reporters"]<a href="/?page_id=2505">L’UNICEF, en appui au gouvernement congolais, donne la parole aux jeunes en RDC pour qu’ils défendent les droits de l’enfant et soient acteurs des décisions qui les concernent</a>.[/section]\n\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Principaux programmes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'principaux-programmes', '', '', '2013-12-10 13:42:37', '2013-12-10 13:42:37', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=2940', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(2950, 1, '2013-12-10 14:04:53', '2013-12-10 14:04:53', '[one_half] <strong>Les principaux chiffres clefs sur la situation des enfants de la RDC. </strong>\n\nDans cette section vous trouverez les données essentielles pour mieux apprehender le contexte, les progress realisés et le chemin à parcourir pour que l''ensemble des droits des enfants de la RDC soient respectés.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[/one_half]\n\n[one_half_last]\n\n[accordion]\n\n[section title="Principaux chiffres clefs"] <a href="/?page_id=2724">Les données clefs concernant les progrès réalisés vers les Objectifs Millénaire pour le Développement ainsi que la situation des enfants de RDC dans un seul document </a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Education"]<a href="/?page_id=2437">Les principaux chiffres clefs en matière d''éducation</a>[/section]\n\n[section title="Santé"]<a href="/?page_id=2211">Les principaux chiffres clefs en matière de Santé</a>.[/section]\n\n[section title="Nutrition"]<a href="/?page_id=2484">Les principaux chiffres clefs en matière de Nutrition</a>.[/section]\n\n[section title="Protection"]<a href="/?page_id=2387">Les principaux chiffres clefs en matière de Protection</a>.[/section]\n\n[section title="Urgences"]<a href="/?page_id=2465">Les principaux chiffres clefs en matière d''Urgences</a>.[/section]\n\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Chiffres clefs', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'chiffres-clefs', '', '', '2013-12-10 14:04:53', '2013-12-10 14:04:53', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=2950', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3242, 1, '2013-12-23 15:31:45', '2013-12-23 15:31:45', '', 'Children''s voice', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'childrens-voice', '', '', '2013-12-23 15:31:45', '2013-12-23 15:31:45', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3242', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3357, 1, '2013-12-27 15:27:10', '2013-12-27 15:27:10', '<a href="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/ZAI_Mbandaka_23-March-2011-307.jpg"><img alt="ZAI_Mbandaka_23 March 2011 307" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/ZAI_Mbandaka_23-March-2011-307.jpg" width="640" height="475" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>IMPROVE WATER SUPPLY AND SANITATION</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In DRC as in many countries around the world, UNICEF is working to improve water supply and sanitation in schools and communities and to promote hygienic practices . We support multiple and diverse activities and cooperate with many partners, including families, communities, governments and organizations sharing the same values.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>INTERVENTION IN EMERGENCIES</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">We provide emergency assistance to communities and people at risk of not being supplied with water and threatened by disease emergency. All programs of UNICEF''s water and sanitation are designed to contribute to the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals related to water and sanitation : reduce, by 2015, the proportion of people without sustainable access to safe water and basic sanitation.</p>', 'Water and Sanitation', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'water-and-sanitation', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:21:49', '2014-02-16 16:21:49', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3357', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3361, 1, '2013-12-27 15:33:03', '2013-12-27 15:33:03', '<img alt="NYHQ2000-0682" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/UNI35078.jpg" />\r\n\r\n<strong> 4 MILLION PEOPLE WILL GAIN ACCESS TO IMPROVED WATER AND SANITATION SERVICES BY 2017</strong>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The UNICEF Country Programme 2013-2017 extended the Healthy Villages and Schools program to almost 6,000 villages and 1,500 schools, the equivalent of approximately 4 million people gaining first-time access to improved WASH services.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">By September 30, 2019, UNICEF planned to reach 7500 villages which will have committees acting to protect and maintain their healthy environment</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The HVHS programme is scaling up to be operational in 250 out of the 515 Health Zones (49%). The second phase of the Healthy Villages and Schools program is focusing on sustainability, including the sustainability of hardware WASH installations; institutional capacity, accountability and obligation, health outcomes, and the scalability of quality results. A strategy is being defined to promote complementarity between the programme and projects of other government institutions, NGOs or the private sector.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">To promote transition between emergency and development, new strategies are under discussion within the different stakeholders. UNICEF is also supporting the 2013-2017 New Multisectoral Strategic Plan for the Elimination of Cholera in DRC.</p>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Water and Sanitation - The way forward in DRC', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'water-and-sanitation-the-way-forward-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:22:32', '2014-02-16 16:22:32', '', 3357, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3361', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3365, 1, '2013-12-27 15:39:18', '2013-12-27 15:39:18', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/110921095256.jpg"><img class="alignleft" alt="110921095256" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/110921095256-242x300.jpg" width="242" height="300" /></a>DRC is not on track to reach the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) in water and sanitation. The achievement of Goal 7 would require reaching 72% access to drinking water and 58% access to improved sanitation by 2015. Currently 47% of the population has access to safe drinking water (83% urban and 31% rural), while only 14% of the population has access to adequate sanitation facilities (36% urban and 4% rural) according to MICS 2010. Thus to meet the MDGs 17.5 million people in DRC would need to gain access to water and 30.8 million people must gain access to sanitation by 2015.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>MAIN KEY STATISTICS</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>-</strong> <strong>47 %</strong> of the total population has access to safe drinking water, and <strong>14%</strong> access to improved sanitation (MICS 2010).</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">- In rural areas, water coverage is <strong>31 %</strong>; rural improved sanitation <strong>4%</strong> (MICS 2010).</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">- In addition, there are cholera epidemics in endemic cholera prone zone every year in the provinces of Katanga, Oriental, North and South Kivu. DRC is also facing outbreaks in non-endemic areas along the river Congo or cross border with Zambia/Congo Brazzaville. In August 2013, 21 264 cholera cases with 321 deaths have been reported in total and half of them came from Katanga Province and cross-border with Zambia (2014 HNO).</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">- <strong>2.7 millions of IDP’s</strong> are facing challenges to meet their right to get access to safe water, improved sanitation and hygiene</p>', 'Water and Sanitation - Key statistics', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'water-and-sanitation-key-statistics', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:22:17', '2014-02-16 16:22:17', '', 3357, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3365', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3370, 1, '2013-12-27 15:43:47', '2013-12-27 15:43:47', '<img class="alignleft" alt="2" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/2-300x199.jpg" width="300" height="199" />\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The water and sanitation sector is weakened by a fragmented political structure. There are currently 6 different government bodies implicated, through 6 separate ministries. Major agencies include: REGIDESO for urban water (Ministry of Energy); National Hydraulic Service for rural water (SNHR), Ministry of Rural Development; PNA for sanitation (Ministry of the Environment) and the 9th Bureau of the Ministry of Health working in both water and sanitation. To facilitate the coordination of the water and sanitation sector, a separate agency, the CNAEA, was created in the 1990s and is based at the Ministry of Planning.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Support was given to the National Committee for Action on Water and Sanitation under the Ministry of Plan (CNAEA), for DRC to join 35 other countries as members of the Sanitation and Water for All initiative. The Government committed at the Washington high level conference in April 2012 to strengthen WASH institutions and related human resources in 2013-2014. UNICEF participates in the WASH Donor Group and the Hygiene Thematic Group. Among the priorities promoted by UNICEF are to push for support to the government strategy on the elimination of cholera in endemic and epidemic areas.</p>', 'Water and Sanitation - Key Challenges in DRC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'water-and-sanitation-key-challenges-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:21:33', '2014-02-16 16:21:33', '', 3357, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3370', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3372, 1, '2013-12-27 15:52:53', '2013-12-27 15:52:53', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/3401.jpg"><img alt="340" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/3401.jpg" width="615" height="440" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>In the WASH sector, Unicef and its partner obtained the following results:</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">1. Increased government capacity and development of national strategies towards improving rural water, sanitation and hygiene throughout 11 provinces and 250 health zones of DRC.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">2. The national “Healthy Village and Healthy School” programme follows a community-driven demand-led strategy which gives families the opportunity to make informed choices while strengthening their resilience.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">3. At the end of June 2013 the VEA programme was operational in 11 Provinces, 212 Health Zones, and 5289 villages, of which 3256 were certified “Healthy Villages” and 1425 schools, of which 1054 were certified “Healthy Schools”. These results translate into the concrete results of 2,273,198 new persons gaining access to a healthy environment by surpassing minimum water, sanitation and hygiene targets.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">4. UNICEF WASH emergency programme assisted more than 800 000 persons in cholera-prone zones with preventive as well as WASH cholera-response packages (MYR Sitrep 2013). With the support of RRMP (Reponse Rapide aux Mouvements de Population, UNICEF DRC’s major emergency programme), 295,144 people were given access to water, sanitation and hygiene in emergency from January to Octobre 2013.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">5. In 2013, as UNICEF cluster lead agency for emergency WASH interventions, the WASH Cluster, with their members, coordinated the response to assist more than 4.5 million persons (MYR Sitrep 2013) to get access the WASH packages in order to save life, reduce vulnerability and meet the basic needs.</p>', 'Water and Sanition - Major achievements in DRC', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'water-and-sanition-major-achievements-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '', 3357, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3372', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3376, 1, '2013-12-27 16:03:56', '2013-12-27 16:03:56', '<p style="text-align: justify;">[one_half] <strong>Everything you need to know about the work of UNICEF and its partners in the Democratic Republic of Congo.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In this section you will find all the articles published by our specialists, partners and guests. A unique and authentic vision of the work done on the ground.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">For each topic on which UNICEF works in the DRC you will find an overview, the main key statistics, achievements and the way forward.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The main programs are also detailed and a map will show you where the UNICEF offices are located in DRC.</p>\r\n[/one_half]\r\n\r\n[one_half_last]\r\n\r\n[accordion]\r\n\r\n[section title="Our articles"]All articles written by our experts, partners and guests. A unique and authentic vision of the work on the ground for the children of the DRC<a href="/?cat_ID=126">.</a> [/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Our themes"]For each topic on which UNICEF works in the DRC, find the challenges, main key statistics and results.<a href="/?page_id=2932"> </a>[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Main programmes"] Fact sheets with the most important information on the major programmes implemented by UNICEF in DRC.[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Presence on the ground"]A map of the DRC representing UNICEF offices throughout the territory. [/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Press releases"] Most recent press releases published by UNICEF in DRC[/section]\r\n\r\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Our Work', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'our-work', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:17:03', '2014-02-16 16:17:03', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3376', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3379, 1, '2013-12-27 16:11:19', '2013-12-27 16:11:19', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/eva1.jpg"><img alt="eva" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/eva1-1024x349.jpg" width="625" height="213" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>BACKGROUND AND OBJECTIVE</strong>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Despite the presence of water resources in the DRC, 51 million Congolese people still lack access to safe drinking water - nearly three-quarters of the country''s population. Poor access to drinking water and lack of education on hygiene and sanitation are among the main causes of high morbidity and mortality, especially among children under 5 years.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In order to address these issues water, hygiene and sanitation issues, the DRC government has reinforced its efforts to improve the health conditions in the most vulnerable areas. Thus in 2006 , with the support of its partners including UNICEF, he set up the Healthy Village Programme. An extension to the schools through the Healthy School Programme, has been launched in 2008.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The main objective of the Healthy villages and schools programme is to reduce infant mortality and the spread of water-borne diseases, as well as improve access to drinking water favored in rural and suburban areas.</p>\r\n<strong>WHAT IS A HEALTHY VILLAGE ?</strong>\r\n\r\n1. A village with a dynamic committee\r\n\r\n2. At least 80% of the population has access to drinking water\r\n\r\n3. At least 80% of households use sanitary latrines\r\n\r\n4. At least 80% of plots are clean\r\n\r\n5. At least 60% of the population washes their hands with soap or ash before eating and after visiting the latrine\r\n\r\n6. At least 70% of the population understands the pattern of disease transmission from fecal matter and the associated preventive measures\r\n\r\n7. The village is cleaned at least once a month\r\n\r\n<strong>AND A HEALTHY SCHOOL ?</strong>\r\n\r\n1. 100% of teachers are trained in the "Healthy Schools" strategy, Health and Environmental Education, and 100% of Parent Involvement Committee members have received awareness training\r\n\r\n2. At least 80% of student textbooks are available: 1 textbook for every 2 students or 1 guide per teacher\r\n\r\n3. At least 1 entrance for every 40 girls and 1 entrance for every 50 boys, at least 80% of latrines are sanitary\r\n\r\n4. 100% availability of drinking water and at least 80% of students wash their hands with soap or ash\r\n\r\n5. The schoolyard and classrooms are cleaned once a day and trash is thrown in a refuse pit\r\n\r\n6. 100% of health and environment patrollers elected in the schools have received awareness training and are operational\r\n\r\n<strong>A STEP-BY-STEP GUIDE TO THE "HEALTHY VILLAGE" APPROACH</strong>\r\n\r\n<b></b>1. The community learns of the programme and collectively decides to adopt it, then submits a formal request to the health zone.\r\n\r\n2. A statement of agreement between the community and the health zone is signed.\r\n\r\n3. The health zone provides training to 20 volunteers, then the community elects a village committee.\r\n\r\n4. Health zone officials investigate the behaviours, attitudes and practices of village households.\r\n\r\n5. The community analyses its hygiene and sanitation using community mapping, observation walks, 3 categories of classification for hygiene conditions and an analysis of fecal-oral transmission routes.\r\n\r\n6. The community develops a Community Action Plan and prioritises interventions.\r\n\r\n7. The community takes action to improve access to water and sanitation. Volunteers promote good hygiene practices.\r\n\r\n8. The final investigation: the office of the health zone conducts a study of the community''s new knowledge, attitudes and practices.\r\n\r\n9. The chief medical officer of the health zone checks whether the village meets the standards required to be designated a Healthy Village. If this is the case, the chief medical officer provides the village with a certificate as part of a celebration.\r\n\r\n<strong>You will find more useful information on the healthy village and school official website:</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ecole-village-assainis.cd/"><cite>www.<b>ecole</b>-<b>village</b>-<b>assainis</b>.cd/</cite></a>‎', 'Healthy villages and schools', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'healthy-villages-and-schools', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:12:59', '2014-02-16 16:12:59', '', 3357, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3379', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3385, 1, '2013-12-27 16:38:39', '2013-12-27 16:38:39', '[one_half] <strong>Main key statistic on the situation of DRC''s children.</strong>\r\n\r\nIn this section you will find essential data to better apprehend the context, the progresses that have been made ​​and the way forward to ensure that all children''s rights are respected in the DRC.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/one_half]\r\n\r\n[one_half_last]\r\n\r\n[accordion]\r\n\r\n[section title="Main key statistics"] Key data on the progresses towards the Millennium Development Goals as well as the situation of children in the DRC in a single document[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Education"]<a href="/?page_id=2437">M</a>ain key statistics on Education[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Health"]Main key statistics on Health[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Nutrition"]<a href="/?page_id=2484">Main key statistics on Nutrition</a>.[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Protection"]Main key statistics on<a href="/?page_id=2387"> Protection</a>.[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="Emergencies"]Main key statistics on Emergencies.[/section]\r\n\r\n[/accordion] [/one_half_last]', 'Key Statistics', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'key-statistics', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:19:06', '2014-02-16 16:19:06', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3385', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3388, 1, '2013-12-27 16:48:36', '2013-12-27 16:48:36', '[one_third]\r\n<h4><strong>Jonathan</strong></h4>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://ponabana.com/author/jonathan/"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Profil Jonathan" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Profil-Jonathan1.jpg" width="373" height="249" /></a><em>  Jonathan is 16 years old and he is a youth reporter Kinshasa. He studied at Saint Joseph College and wants to become a lawyer to defend the children''s rights. His dream? That his country "become a country fit for children, a country that respects the rights of the children and put them at the center of everything."</em></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/one_third][one_third]\r\n<h4><strong>Eunice</strong></h4>\r\n<a href="http://www.kidsareheroes.org/heroes/Eunice-Muba.php"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Eunice MUBA," src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Eunice-MUBA-1024x683.jpg" width="375" height="250" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Eunice is 14 years old and she is a youth reporter in Kinshasa. She represented Central Africa''s children  at the African Union Summit in Addis Ababa in 2012. In her speech </em><em>to African leaders</em><em>, she recalled children''s rights to survival, freedom of expression, education, health and called for a strategy to prevent armed conflicts which affect the child. Why youth reporter? "Because I want to make my country a better place for children to live."</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>[/one_third][one_third_last]</h4>\r\n<h4><strong>Samy</strong></h4>\r\n<a href="http://ponabana.com/author/samy/"><img class="aligncenter" alt="samy" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/samy1.jpg" width="422" height="281" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Samy is 10 years old and he is 5th grade in </em><em>Nsango Magulu </em><em>Elementary school, 22 km from the town of Kalemie. He is one of the 40 youth reporters trained in the province of North Katanga in August 2013. He lives with his family in the camps for displaced perons of Nsango Magulu and is from Bendera.</em></p>\r\n<em> </em>[/one_third_last]\r\n\r\n[separator]\r\n\r\n[one_third]\r\n<h4> <em> </em><strong>Rolande</strong></h4>\r\n<a href="http://ponabana.com/author/rolande/"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Bandundu 4" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Bandundu-4.jpg" width="230" height="197" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Rolande is 13 years old and she is a  youth reporter in Bandundu. Along with her friends, she is comitted to fight against early marriage and the economic exploitation of children. Later, she will be a teacher to convey what she has learned</em></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/one_third][one_third]\r\n<h4><strong> </strong></h4>\r\n<h4>[/one_third][one_third_last]</h4>\r\n<h4><em> </em>[/one_third_last]</h4>\r\n[separator]\r\n\r\n<strong>The articles represent the views of their authors and do not engage the responsibility of UNICEF.</strong>', 'Child bloggers', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'bloggers-2', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:10:13', '2014-02-16 16:10:13', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3388', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3521, 1, '2014-01-02 15:59:18', '2014-01-02 15:59:18', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/92.jpg"><img title="Photo © AVSI/2012/Morton" alt="9" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/92.jpg" width="775" height="620" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>EDUCATION IS A FUNDAMENTAL HUMAN RIGHT</strong>\r\n\r\nEducation is a fundamental human right: Every girl and boy in every country is entitled to it. Quality education is critical to development both of societies and of individuals, and it helps pave the way to a successful and productive future. When all children have access to a quality education rooted in human rights and gender equality, it creates a ripple effect of opportunity that influences generations to come.\r\n\r\n<strong>REDUCING INEQUITIES AND DISCRIMINATION</strong>\r\n\r\nEducation ends generational cycles of poverty and disease and provides a foundation for sustainable development. A quality basic education equips girls and boys with the knowledge and skills they need to adopt healthy lifestyles, protect themselves from HIV and take an active role in social, economic and political decision-making as they transition to adolescence and adulthood. Educated adults are more likely to have smaller and healthier families, to be informed about appropriate child-rearing practices and to ensure that their children start school on time and ready to learn.\r\n\r\nEducation based on human rights also helps to root out some of society’s persistent inequities. These deprive millions of children, particularly girls, of quality education – and therefore subject them to a life of missed opportunities. Ensuring equity in education builds a foundation for equal opportunity, economic growth, employment creation and productivity.\r\n\r\n<strong>AN OPPORTUNITY TO SURVIVE, DEVELOP AND REACH THEIR FULL POTENTIAL</strong>\r\n\r\nUNICEF supports development of national capacities to reduce gender and other disparities and discrimination against children who are out of school. This includes girls; children from poor households or living in rural areas; children belonging to ethnic and linguistic minorities, indigenous groups and castes facing discrimination; and children affected by HIV/AIDS or disabilities.\r\n\r\nFor UNICEF, equity means that all children have an opportunity to survive, develop and reach their full potential, without discrimination, bias or favoritism. This interpretation is consistent with the Convention on the Rights of the Child, which pledges the fundamental rights of every child.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Education', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'education', '', '', '2014-02-14 14:25:06', '2014-02-14 14:25:06', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3521', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3525, 1, '2014-01-02 16:12:52', '2014-01-02 16:12:52', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/141.jpg"><img alt="Pupils on their way to school; at Plateau neighborhood, in Kikwit." src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/141.jpg" width="645" height="430" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>"REDUCING THE NUMBER OF CHILDREN OUT OF SCHOOL"</strong>\r\n<div style="text-align: justify;">\r\n\r\nFollowing the Education First High level meeting, a number of partners have pledged to support the acceleration of primary education in DRC. Within the framework of the Interim Education Plan, the recently approved GPE funding ($ 100 millions), complemented by other external resources (including UNICEF’s , DFID AFD, World Bank, USAID, Educate and Child/Qatar) will contribute a number of measures to fill existing financing gaps. UNICEF and DFID are supporting the elaboration of the Equity in Education policy and strategy to reduce the number of children out of school. AFD will support recurrent costs (especially teachers’ salaries, construction and rehabilitation of schools as well as quality education); USAID will also contribute to the Education First Initiative, focusing on Equitable Access and Quality.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nImportant steps to take include an increase of budget allocations for the education sector, increased investments in access and quality, especially dealing with the systemic challenges affecting teachers. . A budget monitoring and an accountability systemneed strengthening, including through promotion of local community participation in policy dialogue. . The capacity of all stakeholders in relation to financial and program management must be enhanced. The Information System for Management Education (EMIS) needs to be strengthened and government investments made to sustain routine collection and analysis of data. . UNICEF is currently supporting EMIS capacity strengthening at decentralized levels.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Education - The way forward in DRC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'education-the-way-forward-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '', 3521, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3525', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3531, 1, '2014-01-02 16:29:44', '2014-01-02 16:29:44', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/161.jpg"><img alt="16" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/161.jpg" width="773" height="515" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> </b>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223"><b>Indicateurs</b><b></b></td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258"><b>Données</b></td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190"><b>Année/Source</b><b></b></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Preschool enrollment rate 3.6%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">3,6%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Net Intake Rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=59%  G=52,9% T=56%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Gross enrollment rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=99,6% G=85,8% T=92,7%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Completion rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=68,5% G=49,1% T=58,8%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Parity Index</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">0,86</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Children (5-17 years) out of  school</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">7.4 millions (52% filles) ; 60% ont 6 et 7 ans</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Out of school Study 2012</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Transition from primary to secondary</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">74.7% (Gross rate)</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Gross enrollment  rate in secondary school</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">38,5%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Despite decades of economic and political crisis the coverage and performance of the education sector has increased in recent years. Although there is gender parity in enrolment at at primary level, important differences between provinces remain.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>EDUCATION COSTS ARE TOO HIGH</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Primary school completion rate has reached 58,8% in 2011. In spite of the fee free primary education policy,  education costs remains high for families. Government transfers to support the functionning of schools and administrative offices remains insufficient. Pupils are  requested to pay different types of fees including teachers’ salaries.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">After Nigeria and Ethiopia,  DRC has the largest number of school-children in sub-Saharan Africa. The 2012 Out of School study shows a direct relationship between the enrolment of children in school and the income status of a household. In poor families the access and retention of children is low, especially in rural areas, gender parity is 0.86 – and of those who reach university level, girls constitute only 30%</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EAD-2012-Enfants-en-dehors-de-lEcole-par-province-en-RDC1.jpg"><img alt="EAD 2012 Enfants en dehors de l''Ecole par province en RDC" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EAD-2012-Enfants-en-dehors-de-lEcole-par-province-en-RDC1.jpg" width="960" height="720" /></a>', 'Education - Key Statistics', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'education', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '', 3521, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3531', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3536, 1, '2014-01-02 16:50:38', '2014-01-02 16:50:38', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/131.jpg"><img alt="Girl smiling - the flower she wears on her forehead is for the International Women Day; at Kakoy Primary School, in Kakoy." src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/131.jpg" width="630" height="420" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>SCHOOL COSTS ARE TOO HIGH</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In 2010 a policy of school fee abolition was announced by the President yet its impact is limited Parents continue to bear the main burden of direct and indirect cost, including the running costs of schools and the incentives for teachers who are not on the official payroll or who are paid late. . UNICEF is assisting in the formative evaluation of this policy with a view to guiding policy re-orientations.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>EDUCATION IN THE NATIONAL BUDGET</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Over 2008-2010, the budget of the education sector accounted for about 3% of GDP and only 8.5% of the national budget. Although the education’s share of the national budget has increased to 13% in 2013, most domestic funding goes to pay salaries (see Interim Education Plan 2012/2016)  The body of teachers represents 80% of the size of the education public sector, while funding for other items such as operations and investments remain weak and often ineffective. There is an estimated gap of $270 million that is yet to be funded by the Government’s Interim Education Plan.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>QUALITY AND INVESTMENTS</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Children lack basic competencies and the more a student progresses on the educational ladder, the lower the retention rates. Major quality concerns include the lack of investments in initial teacher training, and incentives to attract good quality persons into the teaching profession. The curriculum is over-loaded with content that is irrelevant for 21<sup>st</sup> century needs , especially in terms of employable economic, social and emotional skills . UNICEF and partners are working toegther to support improvement of reading literacy, numeracy and life skills as core foundational skills. UNICEF is also supporting a new Peace Building in Education Programme which will strengthen the resilience of children, their parents and institutions to prevent, manage, and deal with conflicts and violence in and around schools.</p>', 'Education - Key Challenges in DRC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'education-key-challenges-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '', 3521, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3536', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(3541, 1, '2014-01-02 16:57:30', '2014-01-02 16:57:30', '<img alt="15" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/151.jpg" width="718" height="478" />\r\n\r\n<strong>IMPROVEMENT OF THE EDUCATION QUALITY</strong>\r\n\r\nOver the past four years (2008-2012), UNICEF has contributed over $ 80 million U.S. dollars to increase access and improve the quality of education for  more than 4 million children. During the 2012-2013 school-year UNICEF has invested more than 1.7 million dollars in school kits for 623,466 students and 14,922 teachers in the South and the West of the country.\r\n\r\n<strong>EDUCATION IN EMERGENCIES</strong>\r\n\r\nIn the conflict-affected East, direct cash transfer of funds to schools was done for a total of $ 650,000 in favor of school kits for 346.773 students and 7,677 teachers. To promote education in emergency and transition situations UNICEF trained teachers and parents on learner-centred methodologies in core curricula areas and psychosocial support for children affected by the conflict, thereby contributing to improved learner performance.\r\n\r\nAmong the 2.4 million internally displaced persons (IDP), half are children and 690,000 are old enough to attend primary school. The enrollment rate of children in IDP camps is around 37% (Sources: OCHA IDP Factsheet, July 2012). However, enrolment rates in the provinces affected by conflict compare favourably with non-emergency provinces thanks to emergency education support provided by various donors.\r\n\r\n<strong>ENHANCED PARTNERSHIPS</strong>\r\n\r\nAt policy level, UNICEF has contributed to improve knowledge on equity issues in education and the elaboration of policies and strategies to combat exclusion in education. UNICEF has also been instrumental in improvements in sector coordination among all partners as well as the development of a policy dialogue agenda to accompany sector reform. Sector analysis is currently ongoing with UNICEF support, which for the first time will produce a conflict-sensitive analysis to be used in the elaboration of the new education sector plan.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Education - Major achievements in DRC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'education-major-achievements-in-drc', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '', 3521, 'http://ponabana.com/?page_id=3541', 0, 'page', '', 0);
