(5052, 1, '2014-01-17 08:41:11', '2014-01-17 08:41:11', 'UNICEF assists internally displaced persons with disabilities\nGoma, Democratic Republic of the Congo, 25 May 2013 - “The wheelchair Meshak has received is very important as it’s very difficult for him to walk,” says Aline Vumilia, 22, as Meshak Batundi sits in a wheelchair for the first time and starts learning how to pedal.  “He’s also received an adapted toilet because his access to public latrines is difficult too,” Vumilia adds. \n\n8-year old Meshak walks on his knees because he contracted a disease that maimed his two feet and his right hand.  The young boy lives with his aunt Aline at Lac Vert Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) site near North Kivu’s capital Goma.  He was separated from his mother when armed conflict reached his village of Kitchanga last December. \n\nRestoring dignity\nThere are hundreds of people with disabilities amongst the thousands of displaced people who have settled around Goma, having fled from armed conflict in North Kivu, eastern DRC.  Basic services available at the IDP site pose accessibility problems to people with disabilities.  So, additional measures are required to make sure that these people have equal access to facilities and are able to live with dignity. \nThrough the Rapid Response to Population Movements (RRMP) mechanism, UNICEF’s partner, Handicap International, distributes items such as crutches, walking canes, wheelchairs and adapted toilets. “Now that they move on wheelchairs, these people who used to walk on all fours can get together with people more easily,” underlines Odette Katungo, a Handicap International physiotherapist. “Their dignity is restored,” she adds.\nRRMP assisted over 1.5 million conflict-affected people in 2012\nThe RRMP delivers an integrated assistance to acutely vulnerable populations affected by displacement, return and/or natural disasters—including host families—while there are sites of displaced persons in some provinces, like Nord Kivu where Meshak and his aunt live, over 80% of IDPs in the D.R.Congo do not live in sites or camps, but with host families.  In partnership with OCHA and through seven stand-by INGO partners in Province Orientale, Katanga, North and South Kivu provinces, RRMP assisted over 1.5 million emergency-affected people in 2012 with access to water, hygiene and sanitation, essential household items, education and health services.\nThe UNICEF/Handicap International RRMP project targets 300 displaced persons with disabilities living at Lac Vert and Bulengo, two IDP sites on the outskirts of Goma.  “Among the displaced people here, there are persons living with disabilities who find it difficult to move or use the latrines,” Katungo explains.  “That’s why Handicap International decided to provide them with different types of items to assist with mobility and walking,” she adds.  Displaced people living with disabilities are among the most vulnerable. UNICEF and its partners aim at reducing such vulnerability and improve their living conditions on the IDP sites or with host families until peace and security allow for their return to their villages of origin.\n[END]', 'UNICEF assists internally displaced persons with disabilitiesGoma, Democratic Republic of the Congo, 25 May 2013 - ?The wheelchair Meshak has received is very important as it?s very difficult for him to walk,? says Aline Vumilia, 22, as Meshak Batundi sits in a wheelchair for the first time and starts learning how to pedal.  ?He?s also received an adapted toilet because his access to public latrines is difficult too,? Vumilia adds. 8-year old Meshak walks on his knees because he contracted a disease that maimed his two feet and his right hand.  The young boy lives with his aunt Aline at Lac Vert Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) site near North Kivu?s capital Goma.  He was separated from his mother when armed conflict reached his village of Kitchanga last December. Restoring dignityThere are hundreds of people w