(4877, 1, '2013-12-07 16:08:55', '2013-12-07 16:08:55', 'Children play at the Child Friendly Space (CFS) operated by UNICEF partner AVSI in the Bulengo IDP site. The CFS provide a safe environment for children to gather for recreational and educational activities while not in school.\n\nA delegation of Emergency Directors including UNICEF Director of Emergency Programs Ted Chaiban, OCHA Operations Director John Ging, UN Humanitarian Coordinator in DRC Moustapha Soumare and high-level representatives from WFP, WHO, FAO and UNHCR visited the Bulengo Spontaneous Site just outside Goma on Tuesday, October 22, 2013 to witness the multi-agency humanitarian response in the largest single displacement site in North Kivu. \n\nHome to approximately 55,000 Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) Bulengo has experienced a massive influx of IDPs since November 2012 when thousands fled towards Goma during fighting between the M23 and Congolese Army (FARDC). Since then, numerous waves of displacement have resulted from clashes between the FARDC and M23, Nyatura and APCLS rebel groups. Coming mainly from the Masisi and Rutshuru territories, the IDPs in Bulengo represent some of the more than 1 million currently displaced in North Kivu. \n\nCoordinated by IOM and managed by Première Urgence – Aide Médicale International (PU-AMI) and Danish Refugee Council (DRC) residents of the Bulengo Site have received Non-Food Item (NFI) support  from the UNICEF-OCHA RRMP in December 2012, Food and Nutrition support from WFP and World Vision, Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) support from Oxfam and Mercy Corps, Education and Child Protection support from UNICEF partner AVSI and Health support from MSF Belgium.', 'Children play at the Child Friendly Space (CFS) operated by UNICEF partner AVSI in the Bulengo IDP site. The CFS provide a safe environment for children to gather for recreational and educational activities while not in school.A delegation of Emergency Directors including UNICEF Director of Emergency Programs Ted Chaiban, OCHA Operations Director John Ging, UN Humanitarian Coordinator in DRC Moustapha Soumare and high-level representatives from WFP, WHO, FAO and UNHCR visited the Bulengo Spontaneous Site just outside Goma on Tuesday, October 22, 2013 to witness the multi-agency humanitarian response in the largest single displacement site in North Kivu. Home to approximately 55,000 Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) Bulengo has experienced a massive influx of IDPs since November 2012 when thousands fled towards Goma during fighting between the M23 and Congolese Army (FARDC). Since then, numerous waves of displacement have resulted from clashes between the FARDC and M23, Nyatura and APCLS rebel groups. Coming mainly from the Masisi and Rutshuru territories, the IDPs in Bulengo represent some of the more than 1 million currently displaced in North Kivu. Coordinated by IOM and managed by Première Urgence ? Aide Médicale International (PU-AMI) and Danish Refugee Council (DRC) residents of the Bulengo Site have received Non-Food Item (NFI) support  from the UNICEF-OCHA RRMP in December 2012, Food and Nutrition support from WFP and World Vision, Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) support from Oxfam and Mercy Corps, Education and Child Protection support from UNICEF partner AVSI and Health support from MSF Belgium.', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'children-play-at-the-child-friendly-space-cfs-operated-by-unicef-partner-avsi-in-the-bulengo-idp-site-the-cfs-provide-a-safe-environment-for-children-to-gather-for-recreational-and-educational-acti-2', '', '', '2013-12-07 16:08:55', '2013-12-07 16:08:55', '', 0, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Sitrep1.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
