(4757, 1, '2013-05-16 15:51:45', '2013-05-16 15:51:45', 'On 11 August 2000, a girl stands smiling in the south-central town of Kananga, where members of the local mobile vaccination team are going from door to door during the NIDs campaign against polio to find children who have not yet been immunized against the virus.\n\nFrom 10 to 13 August 2000, UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy visited the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), to further global efforts to eradicate polio, especially in countries affected by conflict. One of 20 priority countries where wild poliovirus is still endemic, her visit there coincided with a National Immunization Days (NIDs) campaign targeting 11 million children. Polio eradication efforts in the country are hampered by ongoing armed conflict in six provinces affecting some 14 million Congolese, as both the national economy and health system are deteriorating. Child malnutrition in all parts of the country is rising; some 20,000 children have been recruited as child soldiers and another 20,000 have been separated from their families; 50,000 are living or working on the streets, with some forced into prostitution, including children younger than eight years old; and approximately 210,000 more are internally displaced.  During her visit, Ms. Bellamy participated in a NIDs launch, as well as in door-to-door outreach efforts to immunize the 10-20 per cent of children unable to go to the central immunization sites, and met with polio-afflicted children, government representatives and UNICEF staff. This is the second round of polio immunizations in the country in the year 2000; a third round is scheduled for September. Each child must be immunized three times to be fully protected from the polio virus.', 'NYHQ2000-0682', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'nyhq2000-0682-2', '', '', '2013-05-16 15:51:45', '2013-05-16 15:51:45', '', 0, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/UNI35078.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
