(4064, 1, '2014-01-22 15:08:17', '2014-01-22 15:08:17', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Aujourd''hui, nous avons visité le site de déplacés internes de Lagabo, à 30 km de Bunia, la capitale la Province Orientale. On y accède par des routes poussiéreuses parcourant des collines couvertes d''herbe. En Août 2013, les combats entre l''armée nationale (FARDC) et les milices locales avaient causé le déplacement de plus de 120 000 personnes sur le territoire d''Irumu. En quelques jours, la population de Lagabo était alors passée de quelques centaines de personnes à près de 23 000 déplacés internes.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Malgré toutes ces difficultés récentes, nous avons rencontré une population chaleureuse et accueillante qui nous a guidé dans leur village, nous offrant l''occasion de discuter des nombreuses façons qui leur avaient permis de faire face à l''adversité, ainsi que de l''importance des efforts humanitaires conjoints dans la région.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/1611.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-4085 aligncenter" alt="16" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/1611.jpg" width="373" height="373" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>"L''ECOLE PRIMAIRE DE LAPA EST PASSÉE DE 11 A 1395 ÉLÈVES EN QUELQUES SEMAINES..."</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Nous nous sommes ensuite rendu à l''école primaire Lapa, une école qui est passée de 11 à 1 395 élèves au moment où les déplacements étaient les plus importants. Nous avons vu les salles de classe qui ont été construites, avons parlé avec les enseignants qui ont été formés, et aux étudiants qui ont reçu des kits scolaires grâce au programme cogéré par l'' UNICEF et OCHA de Réponse Rapide aux Mouvements de Population (RRMP). Le directeur de l''école , M. Kangako nous a expliqué que sans l''appui fourni, ces enfants ne seraient pas en mesure de pouvoir aller à l''école.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/541.jpg"><img class="alignright" alt="5" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/541.jpg" width="309" height="309" /></a>Entre notre visite du centre de santé et celle de la source de l''eau, j''ai eu la chance de parler avec Esther. Cette mère de huit enfants a non seulement été déplacée, mais elle a aussi été séparée de sa famille pendant deux semaines avant la réunification à Lagabo. Toujours déplacée, elle nous a raconté à quel point il a été difficile de pourvoir aux besoins de sa famille alors qu''elle avait été contrainte de laisser tous ses biens derrière elle.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Les matelas, bâches en plastique, accessoires de cuisine qu''elle a reçu dans le cadre d''une foire en articles ménagers essentiels l''ont beaucoup aidé, nous a-t-elle expliqué mais ce qu''elle espère par dessus c''est de pouvoir rentrer chez elle.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>NOUS CONTINUERONS A TRAVAILLER SANS RELÂCHE POUR RÉPONDRE AUX BESOINS LES PLUS URGENTS</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Alors que je parlai avec les membres de cette communauté, j''ai été impressionnée par leur force et leur résilience. Il est clair que l''aide humanitaire demeure un outil important pour cette communauté. Lorsqu''il est combiné avec le travail intensif de l''ensemble de la communauté, de grandes différences peuvent être faites. Nous leur avons envoyé un message clair : l''ensemble de nos équipes aux côtés de nos partenaires continueront à s''engager et à travailler sans relâche pour répondre aux besoins les plus urgents des familles déplacées et de leurs communautés d''accueil.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">A l''heure de rencontrer les autorités locales, nous les avons félicité pour l''engagement dont ils faisaient preuve dans leur travail. Nous les avons encouragés à poursuivre sur cette voie et à continuer d''assurer la sécurité de nos équipes et partenaires, une sécurité essentielle afin de garantir l''accès aux familles qui ont le plus besoin de soutien.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/351.jpg"><img class="alignleft" alt="3" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/351.jpg" width="298" height="298" /></a>J''ai été impressionnée par Lagabo, l''engagement et la détermination que j''ai rencontré. Je me rappellerai longtemps du message repris par de nombreuses personnes durant cette journée: "Il ne peut y avoir de développement sans paix". Cette journée a été l''occasion de mieux comprendre les dures réalités du déplacement alors que nous recherchons des moyens pour continuer d''améliorer nos efforts communs.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Demain nous nous dirigerons vers Goma, la capitale du Nord-Kivu. L''occasion de nous entretenir avec le Gouverneur et d''aller à la rencontre des familles déplacées vivant autour de la ville ... Un tout nouveau contexte, pour une journée qui s''annonce tout aussi intense.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">[separator]\n<strong>This article is available in English on our Facebook page :</strong> <a href="https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.620976734617688.1073741849.149925238389509&amp;type=1" target="_blank">"There can be no development without peace"</a></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n[gallery type="slideshow" ids="4070,4071,4072,4073,4074,4075,4076,4077,4078,4079,4080,4081,4082,4083,4084,4085,4086,4087,4088,4089"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', '"Il ne peut y avoir de développement sans paix"', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'il-ne-peut-y-avoir-de-developpement-sans-paix', '', '', '2014-01-22 15:08:17', '2014-01-22 15:08:17', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=4064', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3986, 1, '2014-01-21 09:30:31', '2014-01-21 09:30:31', '… Yesterday evening I went with friends and colleagues to a screening of the film <em>Benda Bilili ! </em>at the French cultural centre : it was fun, pleasantly funny, moving as well because it showed us this city in which we live, these men, women and children that we see around us without noticing them the majority of the time. In any case, this is very much the ambiance of the film. It’s Kinshasa, it’s my new home. I therefore strongly recommend you see this film if you want to have a bit more of a concrete idea of the context. Some of the scenes in the film are even filmed at the French cultural centre where yesterday we were in the company of the directors, and where a good number of more or less formal events are organised.\n\n<strong>AN EXTREMELY INTERESTING WORLD TO OBSERVE, SOMETIMES REVOLTING, SOMETIMES FASCINATING</strong>\n\nAnother pleasant surprise from yesterday evening was that I realised I have started to get to know a good number of people… it’s not Kigali, Yaoundé, Harare or even Brazza just on the other side of the river. Here, it’s a humanitarian <i>hub</i>, the country is a real continent and you really meet all sorts of people. The whole array of humanity seems to be represented… a real godsend !\n\nIn the same place where you go out with a mate, you can just as well engage in a conversation with investor working for themselves (on the march for the country’s natural resources or property developers from Libya, China, ….), expatriates from Nestle or Canal +, the diplomat freshly dispatched from their capital, the adventurous photographer, the slightly shady mercenary, the presumptuous UN official or the Western living their own story of exotic love… it’s an extremely interesting world to observe, sometimes revolting, sometimes fascinating !\n\n<strong>HERE WE ARE ALONE ALL TOGETHER</strong>\n\nHowever it’s not a ‘life’ as one would normally understand it. Here we are all alone, or rather, all alone together. Lots have been married but are no longer, others manage to maintain a relationship beyond the borders, and then others don’t even try… People suffer from that, a sort of expatriate syndrome of always moving forward, the majority of the time alone, for passion, for ‘the mission’, or just because the life here gives you out of the ordinary adrenaline, and you forget that the rest of the world continues to go on in spite of the « morass »/ « happiness » (it depends on the day) to which you give your body and soul.\n\nTo be continued…\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Illustration by Winnie de Schaetzen for Pona Bana</strong>', 'Travel journal from DR Congo – Episode 4: Surprising encounters', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'travel-journal-from-dr-congo-episode-4-surprising-encounters', '', '', '2014-01-21 09:30:31', '2014-01-21 09:30:31', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3986', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(4010, 1, '2014-01-21 17:17:39', '2014-01-21 17:17:39', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>Cette semaine, Pona Bana reçoit une invitée d''exception, la Directrice Générale adjointe de l''Unicef, Yoka Brandt. Venue en RDC afin d''évaluer les besoins et encourager l''ensemble des partenaires à redoubler d''efforts pour venir en aide aux victimes des conflits sévissant à l''Est du pays elle tâchera de faire passer un message aux plus hautes autorités: les enfants et les femmes doivent être protégés de la violence, en toutes circonstances.</em></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>[separator]\n</em>"Je suis heureuse d''être de retour en RDC; Cela faisait longtemps que je ne m''étais pas rendue à Goma et Bunia et je suis curieuse de voir quels changements ont eu lieu et de me faire une meilleure idée de la situation. A l''Est du pays, la crise humanitaire se poursuit. Il convient de le rappeler et de montrer que nous devons à la fois répondre à cette crise mais aussi aider la résilience des familles affectées.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Mon voyage est organisé conjointement avec l’assistant du Haut Commissionaire aux Opérations du HCR, Janet Lim et du Directeur Exécutif adjoint du PAM, Ramiro Lopes da Silva. Il débute aujourd''hui par Kinshasa.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Déjà, sur le chemin de l''aéroport, je peux m''apercevoir de tous les changements qui sont en cours. Nous avons rendez-vous avec le Premier Ministre de la RDC, Monsieur Matata Ponyo et le Ministre des Affaires Etrangères Monsieur Tshibanda N’Tungamulungo. Nous leur avons réaffirmé notre soutien sans faille dans leurs efforts pour rétablir la paix et avons rappelé notre engagement pour répondre aux besoins des enfants de RDC. Par ailleurs, nous leur avons dit que nous comptions nous aussi sur le gouvernement de RDC pour investir dans leur plus grande richesse, les enfants, et nous avons souligné l’importance de disposer d’un accès humanitaire sécurisé pour le personnel de l’UNICEF sur l’ensemble du territoire.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Nous avons ensuite rencontré Monsieur Kobler, le Représentant du Secrétaire Général des Nations Unies avec qui nous avons évoqué le travail de l’Unicef et des agences dans un contexte de Mission intégrée.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Pour terminer cette intéressante première journée, je me suis rendue à l''Unicef pour rencontrer l’ensemble du personnel. Nos échanges sur la coopération entre agences de l’ONU et l’importance de donner de la voix aux enfants ont été très enrichissants.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Demain nous serons sur le terrain à Bunia, un endroit très affecté par les combats et la violence. Je vous décrirai les rencontres que nous avons pu y faire et les problèmes que nous avons pu identifier».</p>\n[gallery type="slideshow" ids="4016,4017,4018,4019,4037"]\n\n<em>Crédits photos: Jean Paul Baz</em>', '"La crise humanitaire se poursuit en RDC"', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'la-crise-humanitaire-se-poursuit-en-rdc', '', '', '2014-01-21 17:17:39', '2014-01-21 17:17:39', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=4010', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3954, 1, '2014-01-17 16:18:28', '2014-01-17 16:18:28', '<strong>Family planning is one of the most effective ways to improve women’s and children’s health and survival.</strong>\n\n<strong>Why wait?</strong>\n\n1. Pregnancy before the age of 18 or after the age of 35 increases the health risks for the mother and her baby.\n\n2. For the health of both mothers and children, a woman should wait until her last child is at least 2 years old before becoming pregnant again.\n\n3. The health risks of pregnancy and childbirth increase if a woman has had many pregnancies.\n\n4. Family planning services provide men and women of childbearing age with the knowledge and the means to plan when to begin having children, how many to have, how far apart to have them and when to stop. There are many safe, effective and acceptable methods of planning for and avoiding pregnancy.\n\n5. Both men and women, including adolescents, are responsible for family planning. Both partners need to know about the health benefits of family planning and the available options.\n\n<a href="http://www.unicef.org/publications/index_53254.html">See all Facts for Life.</a>\n\n<em>Illustration by:</em>\n\n<a href="http://maxlewko.blogspot.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="Lewko" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Lewko1.jpg" width="113" height="28" /></a>\n\n<a href="http://maxlewko.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">http://maxlewko.blogspot.com</a>', 'Facts for Life no.1 - Timing births', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'facts-for-life-no-1-timing-births', '', '', '2014-01-17 16:18:28', '2014-01-17 16:18:28', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3954', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3949, 1, '2014-01-17 15:29:15', '2014-01-17 15:29:15', '<strong>Every two weeks, you can learn about the programme in detail!</strong>\n\nThis "Best Practices Guide" will help you to understand what has been accomplished, the key events and the lessons to be learnt. It’s an excellent way to identify not only the challenges we have faced but also the advances that these programmes have made possible.\n\n<strong>CHILD REPORTERS</strong>\n\nFor entry No. 1 of this "Best Practices Guide" we would like you to meet the "Child Reporters".\n\nThey are aged between 12 and 17 years old and they use their pens or cameras to take the floor to ensure that their rights are respected. The programme enables these children to connect with each other and to share and voice their points of view in provincial, national and international arenas.\n\n<strong>In the next "Best Practices Guide" we will show you how UNICEF supports the national back-to-school campaign so that all children can access primary education.</strong>\n<p style="margin: 12px auto 6px auto; font-family: Helvetica,Arial,Sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 14px; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; -x-system-font: none; display: block;"><a style="text-decoration: underline;" title="View Young Reporters FR on Scribd" href="http://fr.scribd.com/doc/192062709/Young-Reporters-FR">Young Reporters FR</a> by <a style="text-decoration: underline;" title="View UNICEFDRC''s profile on Scribd" href="http://www.scribd.com/UNICEFDRC">UNICEFDRC</a></p>\n<iframe id="doc_98751" src="//www.scribd.com/embeds/192062709/content?start_page=1&amp;view_mode=scroll&amp;access_key=key-1ryfq358ob5qph7ik248&amp;show_recommendations=true" height="600" width="100%" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" data-auto-height="false" data-aspect-ratio="1.4211356466877"></iframe>', 'Best Practices Guide No. 1 – Child Reporters', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'best-practices-guide-no-1-child-reporters', '', '', '2014-01-17 15:29:15', '2014-01-17 15:29:15', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3949', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3951, 1, '2014-01-17 15:39:37', '2014-01-17 15:39:37', '<strong><a href="/?p=3271&lang=en">By the end of 2014 almost 51.4 million dollars should have be invested</a> by the government of the Democratic Republic of Congo to equip 200 General Hospitals and 1000 Health Centres with quality medical supplies.</strong>\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/karl11.jpg"><img class="alignright" alt="karl1" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/karl11.jpg" width="129" height="183" /></a>\n\n<strong>Transporting this equipment in the DRC presents an enormous challenge since it involves transporting approximately 420 containers from providers located all over the world to the most remote regions of the DRC. </strong>\n\n<strong> We asked Karl Stahl, our healthcare logistics specialist, three questions about the challenges presented by this kind of delivery.</strong>\n\n<em><strong> How much can 420 containers hold?</strong></em>\n\nThey can hold around 14 000 m<sup>2</sup>. To give you an idea of how much that is: all of the supplies could cover the area of a football pitch 2.8m deep.\n\n<em><strong>What type of equipment needs to be transported?</strong></em>\n\nWe have to transport 200 electrocardiographs, 132 ambulances, 200 radiology kits, 200 universal operating tables, 1600 centrifuges, 15 000 hospital beds with mattresses, 600 gynaecology tables, 200 solar refrigerators and 200 generators, among other equipment. Other equipment is easier to transport, for example microscopes, boxes of instruments for minor surgeries and vaccine carriers.\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Karl-41.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-3069 aligncenter" alt="Karl 4" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Karl-41.jpg" width="358" height="276" /></a></p>\n<em><strong>What is UNICEF''s challenge?</strong></em>\n\nUNICEF is responsible for the whole supply chain from the request stage, through  transport (by sea and air), to reception and stocking, conditioning, technical evaluation of target structures, distribution within the country and even training technicians in Kinshasa to assemble and install the equipment in target health centres.\n\nThe containers will arrive by boat or aeroplane at three points in the country: Kinshasa (6 provinces), Goma (4 provinces) and Lubumbashi (1 province). We will then have to transport the equipment to all of the provinces of the DRC whether by road, air or sea.\n\n<strong>Read about this historic decision by the government of the DRC here:</strong>\n\n<a href="/?p=3271&lang=en">An historic day for healthcare in the DRC</a>', 'Challenge: How to deliver 420 containers of medical supplies in the DRC?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'challenge-how-to-deliver-420-containers-of-medical-supplies-in-the-drc', '', '', '2014-01-17 15:39:37', '2014-01-17 15:39:37', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3951', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3906, 1, '2014-01-18 10:24:02', '2014-01-18 10:24:02', '<p style="text-align: justify;">... Hier soir avec des amis et collègues nous sommes allés à la projection du film <em>Benda Bilili! </em>au centre culturel français: un bon moment, délicieusement drôle, émouvant aussi parce qu’il nous montre cette ville dans laquelle nous vivons, ces hommes, ces femmes et ces enfants que nous voyons autour de nous sans les remarquer la plupart du temps. En tout cas l’ambiance du film c’est tout à fait ça. C’est Kinshasa, c’est mon nouveau chez moi. Alors je vous conseille vraiment de voir ce film si vous voulez vous faire une idée un peu plus concrète du contexte. Certaines scènes du film sont même tournées au Centre culturel français ou nous étions hier en compagnie des réalisateurs, et où sont organisés pas mal d''événements plus ou moins formels.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>UN UNIVERS EXTRÊMEMENT INTÉRESSANT A OBSERVER, TANTÔT RÉVOLTANT TANTÔT PASSIONNANT</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Une autre bonne surprise d’hier au soir, c’est que je me suis rendue compte que je commençais à connaître vraiment pas mal de monde… ce n’est pas Kigali, Yaoundé, Harare ou même Brazza juste de l’autre côté du fleuve. Ici, c’est un <i>hub</i> humanitaire, le pays un vrai continent et on rencontre vraiment toutes sortes de gens. Toute la panoplie humaine semble être représentée… une vraie aubaine !</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Dans un même endroit ou vous sortez prendre un pot vous pouvez très bien engager la conversation avec un investisseur à son propre compte (à l’assaut des richesses naturelles du pays ou promoteur immobilier libanais, chinois,…), l’expat de Nestlé ou de Canal +, le diplomate fraîchement dépêché de sa capitale, l’aventurier(e) photographe, le mercenaire un peu louche, l’onusien présomptueux ou l’occidentale qui vit son histoire d’amour exotique… C’est un univers extrêmement intéressant à observer, tantôt révoltant tantôt passionnant !</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>ICI NOUS SOMMES SEULS TOUS ENSEMBLE</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Pourtant ce n’est pas ‘la vie’ comme on l’entend normalement. Ici nous sommes tous seuls, ou plutôt seuls tous ensemble. Beaucoup ont été mariés mais ne le sont plus, d’autres arrivent à maintenir une relation au-delà des frontières, enfin d’autres n’essayent même pas... Les gens souffrent de ça, d’une sorte de syndrome de l’expat qui a toujours couru vers l’avant, la plupart du temps seul(e), par passion, pour « la mission », ou bien parce que cette vie-là vous procure une adrénaline hors du commun, et que vous en oubliez que le reste du monde continue à tourner hors de votre « bourbier »/ « bonheur » (ça dépend des jours) auquel vous donnez corps et âme.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><em>A suivre...</em></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Illustration réalisée pour Pona Bana par Winnie de Schaetzen</strong>', 'Carnets de route en RD Congo - Episode 4: Des rencontres étonnantes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'carnets-de-route-en-rd-congo-episode-4-des-rencontres-etonnantes', '', '', '2014-01-18 10:24:02', '2014-01-18 10:24:02', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3906', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3946, 1, '2014-01-17 15:21:47', '2014-01-17 15:21:47', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/embouteillage1.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-3166 alignright" title="Road traffick in Kinshasa" alt="embouteillage" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/embouteillage1.jpg" width="230" height="173" /></a>\n\n… the next morning, the UNICEF driver comes looking for me around 7:30. We sit in traffic for half an hour to cover roughly 5 kilometers that separate us from the UNICEF offices (nothing unusual).\n\n<strong>“I HAD BEEN USED TO MY CALM OFFICE IN GENEVA…”</strong>\n\nI situate myself in the corner designated for me, and I am very quickly absorbed by the constant coming and going that fills the office with life! Messengers, colleagues from other departments, government officials… I get the feeling that I will learn much more by following the conversations and other happenings in this busy meeting place than by reading the official UNICEF or department documents. I had been used to my calm and silent office in Geneva, so it requires a lot of effort to concentrate during my first few days in this new work environment.\n\nLittle by little, I get to know my new organization and familiarize myself with its operating style— both rigorous and productive at the same time. My mission? To ensure the quality of the Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene program (commonly called “WASH”) and the consistency of its procedures in achieving effective and sustainable results.\n\n<strong>“THE HEALTHY VILLAGES AND SCHOOLS PROGRAMME… A POWERHOUSE”</strong>\n\nThe program “Healthy Villages and Schools,” guiding light of the WASH department, established an impressive system to monitor its reports and data. A real “powerhouse,” it is capable of analyzing the progress of the project in close to 1500 villages and 700 schools located in 11 different provinces in three operational zones of UNICEF, all in quasi real-time! I have never seen that before at the United Nations. To this capacity for monitoring and evaluation is added the visibly tremendous efficiency of the auditing and communications support functions. I am quite simply in awe!\n\nThe rhythm and discipline of work in this department remind me of operations in the private sector. Horizontality, efficiency, transparency of results… nothing is left except to verify the impact in the field. That development is not far off, because as we learned during the personnel meeting, the current cholera crisis spared the villages enrolled in the program in so far as there are not any reported victims… what better publicity?\n\n<strong>“THE TALK IS FRANK, OPERATIONAL, WITHOUT ANY WAFFLING OR POLITICAL SPEAK”</strong>\n\nI realize quite quickly that I am attached to this style, to this overwhelming commitment. My feelings are enhanced because, beyond the quantity of work completed (in French, the Congolese say “abattu”), there is a real talent among the staff members. Moreover, the talk is frank, operational, without any waffling or political speak. We are here to put a finger on anything that doesn’t work. The discussions go deep down to extract the underlying causes, and we are the first to be outraged by our mistakes. In fact, in four words, it is “not the same job’ …and for me it’s the one that I have always dreamed of doing.\n\nI am impressed with my boss: acute, practical wisdom, based on a rich field experience, but still possessing remarkable humility and accessibility. And the finishing touch for United Nations’ staff with more than twenty years of service: he is still indignant! and he acknowledges it!! “I am not ready to forget about it…”\n\n<i>To be continued…</i>', 'Travel diary in DR Congo - Episode 2 : First day in the office', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'travel-diary-in-dr-congo-episode-2-first-day-in-the-office', '', '', '2014-01-17 15:21:47', '2014-01-17 15:21:47', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3946', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3821, 1, '2014-01-20 11:40:25', '2014-01-20 11:40:25', 'The latest Humanitarian Situation Report has been released. Highlights:\n\n<strong>POLITICAL, SECURITY AND HUMANITARIAN SITUATION</strong>\n\nNATIONAL: <strong>On 30 December coordinated attacks</strong> were carried out against key installations in Kinshasa (including the national television station (RTNC), Ndjili Airport, and a military camp), and in Kindu and Lubumbashi. Although security forces restored order by the end of the day inter-national flights to and from the country were cancelled and over 100 people were reported killed, mostly members of a religious group led by pastor Joseph Mukungubila.\n\nCAR/EQUATEUR: Worsening security situation in Central African Republic since 5 December has resulted in significant refugee movements to DRC, mostly Equateur. From 5 to 31 December an estimated <strong>5,870 new refugees</strong> had arrived, for a total of <strong>54,508 CAR refugees in DRC</strong> (HCR). They are being directed towards 3 refugee sites: Inke (close to Gbadolite), Mole (35km from Zongo) and Buyabo (close to Libenge).\n\nBENI (North-Kivu): <strong>Colonel Mamadou Ndala</strong>, a popular FARDC commander, was killed on January 2 during an attack on his convoy while travelling several kilometers from Beni town.\n\nPINGA/WALIKALE (North-Kivu): <strong>progressive return of displaced population</strong> following reinforced MONUSCO and FARDC presence. 3,646 households (22,587 people) returned to Pinga Centre early December.\n\nKAMANGO/BENI (North-Kivu): Ugandese rebels <strong>ADF-NALU attacked Kamango</strong> on 25 December, leading to new movement of already displaced populations to Nobili.\n\nKATANGA: In December, <strong>12 attacks by Mai Mai</strong> groups registered in dif-ferent localities of Pweto, Manono, Mitwaba and Malemba Nkulu.\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Map-Sitrep-December-20131.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3825 aligncenter" alt="UNICEF DRC Map Sitrep December 2013" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Map-Sitrep-December-20131.jpg" width="623" height="433" /></a>\n\n<strong>KEY FIGURES</strong>\n\nWATER &amp; SANITATION: <strong>2,539,215 persons in cholera-prone zones</strong> benefitting from preventive as well as WASH cholera-response Packages in 2013\n\nEDUCATION: <strong>22,876 more conflict-affected children</strong> now attend school with appropriate materials in Pweto, Katanga.\n\nHEALTH: <strong>13,726 cases of cholera</strong> (lethality of 2.5%) in Katanga in 2013.\n\nNUTRITION: <strong>1,005 ,263 children aged 6-59 months</strong> received Vitamin A supplementation in North-Kivu.\n\nCHILD PROTECTION: <strong>9,683 children survivors of sexual violence</strong> provided with a comprehensive response.\n\nNON FOOD ITEMS: <strong>712,625 displaced persons and host communities</strong> assisted with NFI and shelter material in 2013.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Find out more by reading the full report :</strong>\n\n<strong><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Sitrep-24-Nov-2013-02-Jan-20141.pdf">UNICEF DRC Sitrep 24 Nov 2013 -02 Jan 2014</a></strong>', 'Humanitarian Situation Report - December 2013', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'humanitarian-situation-report-december-2013', '', '', '2014-01-20 11:40:25', '2014-01-20 11:40:25', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3821', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3943, 1, '2014-01-17 14:51:09', '2014-01-17 14:51:09', 'Find us on our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/Unicef-RDC/149925238389509">Facebook </a>page to vote for the 2013 Photo of the Year!\n\n15 photos that provide an opportunity to travel through the provinces of the DRC, meeting Congolese children, were preselected for the contest.\n\nThe picture that receives the most “likes” on Facebook will be designated as “2013 Photo of the Year.”\n\nPlease follow this link to access the contest: <a href="https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.606619532720075.1073741847.149925238389509&amp;type=1">https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.606619532720075.1073741847.149925238389509&amp;type=1</a>\n\nThank you for your participation!\n\n[gallery type="slideshow" ids="3316,3330,3329,3328,3327,3326,3325,3324,3323,3322,3321,3320,3319,3318,3317"]', 'Vote for the 2013 Photo of the Year!!!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vote-for-the-2013-photo-of-the-year', '', '', '2014-01-17 14:51:09', '2014-01-17 14:51:09', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3943', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3749, 1, '2014-01-20 00:00:44', '2014-01-20 00:00:44', '<p style="text-align: left;">Le dernier rapport sur le situation humanitaire a été publié. Points clés:</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>SITUATION POLITIQUE, SÉCURITAIRE ET HUMANITAIRE</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">LE 30 DÉCEMBRE,<em><strong> </strong></em>des<strong> attaques</strong> coordonnées ont pris pour cible des infrastructures clés de Kinshasa (notamment la chaîne de télévision nationale RTNC, l''aéroport de Ndjili et un camp militaire), Kindu et Lubumbashi. L''incident est attribué au Pasteur Joseph Mukungubila. L''ordre a été rétabli dans la journée.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">LES COMBATS EN RÉPUBLIQUE CENTRAFRICAINE ont entraîné l''arrivée de <strong>5 870 nouveaux réfugiés en RDC</strong> du 5 décembre au 31 décembre. Ils seraient maintenant plus de 54 500 dans le pays, principalement en Equateur, où ils sont dirigés vers les sites d''Inke (proche de Gbadolite), Mole (35km de Zongo) et Buyabo (près de Libenge).</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">A BENI (Nord Kivu) le <strong>Colonel Mamadou Ndala a été tué</strong> le 02 janvier. Il avait joué un rôle clé dans l''offensive victorieuse des FARDC contre le M23. L''enquête est toujours en cours, alors que son décès à causé des troubles à Goma notamment.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">A PINGA/WALIKALE<strong> </strong>(Nord Kivu), la présence renforcée des FARDC et de la MONUSCO a amorcé un retour des populations déplacées: déjà <strong>3 646 familles retournées</strong>.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">A KAMANGO/BENI (Nord Kivu), une <strong>attaque des rebelles ADF-NALU</strong> la nuit du 25 décembre a contraint à de nouveaux déplacements de population vers Nobili.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">AU KATANGA enregistrées, à Pweto, Manon, Mitwaba et Malemba Nkulu. 31 congolais ont été rapatriés de Zambie.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Map-Sitrep-December-20131.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3825 alignnone" alt="UNICEF DRC Map Sitrep December 2013" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Map-Sitrep-December-20131.jpg" width="623" height="433" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>CHIFFRES CLÉS</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">EAU ET ASSAINISSEMENT : <strong>2 539 215 personnes</strong> ont bénéficié de paquets de prévention et de réponse au choléra dans les zones affectées en 2013</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">ÉDUCATION : <strong>22 876 enfants</strong> affectés par le conflit de plus vont maintenant à l''école en bénéficiant du matériel approprié à Pweto (Katanga)</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">SANTÉ : <strong>13 726 cas de choléra</strong> (létalité de 2,5 %) ont été enregistrés au Katanga en 2013 .</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">NUTRITION :<em> </em><strong>1 005  263 enfants âgés de 6 à 59 mois</strong> ont reçu une supplémentation en Vitamine A au Nord Kivu en décembre 2013.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">PROTECTION : <strong>9 683 enfants victimes de violence sexuelle</strong> ont bénéficié d''une réponse globale.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">ARTICLES MÉNAGERS ESSENTIELS : <strong>712 625 personnes déplacées et communautés d''accueil</strong> ont été soutenues en articles ménagers essentiels et matériaux de construction en 2013.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Consulter l''intégralité du rapport de situation (en anglais) :</strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><strong><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/UNICEF-DRC-Sitrep-24-Nov-2013-02-Jan-20141.pdf">UNICEF DRC Sitrep 24 Nov 2013 -02 Jan 2014</a></strong></p>', 'Situation humanitaire - Décembre 2013', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'situation-humanitaire-decembre-2013', '', '', '2014-01-20 00:00:44', '2014-01-20 00:00:44', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3749', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3929, 1, '2014-01-17 13:33:32', '2014-01-17 13:33:32', '2013 is finished. It was intense and difficult for a number of families in the DRC.\n\nOne year ago, we saw the end of the capture of Goma by the M23, the displaced persons linked to the armed conflicts converged and the security context was getting worse. The rainy season had caused a worrying cholera epidemic in Lubumbashi and the Katanga province. Today, 2.7 million persons are still displaced, a 35% increase compared to last year.\n\nThe relentless work of our teams, the DRC government and the partners, as well as their adaptability enabled the achievement of important progress and 2014 looks promising.\n\n<strong>17.3 million children vaccinated against polio, 11.2 million children vaccinated against measles</strong>\n\nThere is hope first of all because the mass campaigns bear fruit. In 2013, 17.3 million children were vaccinated against polio and 11.2 million children between 6 months and 10 years old against measles. No new cases of polio have been recorded in 2 years. 200, 000 children under 5 years of age suffering from severe acute malnutrition have been taken care of and 15.3 million children under 5 years of age have been given Vitamin A. More than 1000 villages have obtained the decontaminated village status, an effective barrier against waterborne diseases.\n\n<strong>More than 2.5 million children enrolled in primary school</strong>\n\nThere is also hope because more than 2.5 million children have been enrolled in primary school, a 31% increase compared to 2012 and a promise to build a better future. The registration of births is coupled with the maternity wards, which constitutes an important step regarding the respect of each child’s right to an identity.\n\n<strong>650 00 persons received necessary household items- 4600 children formerly associated with the armed forces and groups were supported</strong>\n\nThere is hope at last because peace looms on the horizon. UNICEF will seize this opportunity. Within the framework of its humanitarian response, UNICEF and its partners have supplied the necessary household items to almost 650 000 persons and 4600 children formerly associated with the armed forces and groups have been supported. We will intensify this action and give support to peace and long-lasting development in order to restore the ability of the communities to look after and protect their children. We stand ready to welcome and reintegrate children that will be, hopefully, many to leave the armed groups.\n\n2014 will also be placed under the sign of innovation. We will launch a program to assess the impact of our actions in the eyes of the beneficiaries via SMS. As for our blog, Pona Bana, it will bring the voice of children from DRC worldwide.\n\n<strong>Enhance the extraordinary potential of DRC</strong>\n\nThe DRC has at its disposal an extraordinary potential that could be the driving force and breadbasket of Africa. We commit ourselves to further increase the efforts in 2014 to leverage the opportunities and stability that the East of the country seems to be gradually regaining.<b></b>\n\nAlready, 2015 and the objectives of the millennium are in sight. The countdown has begun. Together we can construct a better future for all the children of DRC.\n\nOn behalf of everyone at UNICEF, I wish you all an excellent year 2014. That it brings you peace, health and happiness.\n\nPona Bana!', 'Together in 2014 for the children of DRC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'together-in-2014-for-the-children-of-drc', '', '', '2014-01-17 13:33:32', '2014-01-17 13:33:32', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3929', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3941, 1, '2014-01-17 14:41:31', '2014-01-17 14:41:31', '<strong>Sotraki Temporary Site, Goma, 2013.</strong>\n\nDisplaced mothers wait with their children to receive BP-5 and Plumpy Nut nutritional supplements for their malnourished children from UNICEF partner 8<sup>th</sup> CEPAC in Goma.\n\nWhen fighting broke out near Goma in mid-2013, thousands of families fled towards the relative safety of town. With the displaced seeking shelter in schools, churches, and host families, UNICEF coordinated with partners to mobilize resources and provide temporary Non-Food Item and Shelter, Water, Sanitation and Hygiene, Health and Nutrition and logistical support in sites in-and-around Goma.\n\n<strong>From the Photographer:</strong>\n\nAfter the influx of displaced into Goma, the Sotraki Temporary Site was transformed from an empty field into a community of almost 10,000 people within a matter of days. Within about two weeks, the site was back to what it was before, with the displaced moved to more permanent sites. During this two-week period, however, it was almost unbelievable to see the sheer scope of humanitarian needs. Nowhere was this more present than in this tent, with mothers and children gathered  to receive much needed nutritional support.', 'Photo of the Week - 10 January 2014', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'photo-of-the-week-10-january-2014', '', '', '2014-01-17 14:41:31', '2014-01-17 14:41:31', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3941', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3927, 1, '2014-01-17 13:24:56', '2014-01-17 13:24:56', 'By the end of January 2014, 1,250,000 long lasting insecticide treated nets (LLINs) will be distributed in the Maniema Provence. This massive campaign aims to curb malaria prevalence in this heavily affected region.\n\n<strong>1,250,000 MOSQUITO NETS TO PROTECT 2,250,000 INHABITANTS OF MANIEMA</strong>\n\nDuring the campaign, 1,250,000 LLINs will be distributed free of cost to 425,000 homes to protect 2,250,000 Congolese inhabitants of Maniema, particularly children under five years of age and pregnant women. USAID-PMI is financing the campaign and CARITAS CONGO is providing implementation assistance while WFP’s transport network is providing logistical support to deliver the LLINs from Kisangani to all of the health zones of Maniema The campaign is taking place in two stages: the first LLIN distribution in the Kindu and Alunguli health zones was held December 18-24, 2013; the second phase will cover the 16 remaining health zones starting in the second half of January 2014.\n\n<strong>ALL PARTNERS UNITED IN THE FIGHT AGAINST MALARIA</strong>\n\nThe provincial Ministry of Health, led by the Governor of Maniema Provence, launched this campaign in Kindu on Wednesday, December 18, 2013. The event was a great success because the provincial authorities (Provincial Governor and all of the Ministers of the Provincial Government, the President of the Provincial Assembly and all the Provincial Deputies) and the Director of the National Malaria Control Program came together and were able to mobilize more than 500 women from five major religious denominations (Catholic, Protestant, Kimbanguist, Revivalist churches and Islam)\n\n<strong>MALARIA – ONE OF THE MAIN CAUSES OF DEATH FOR CHILDREN UNDER FIVE IN MANIEMA</strong>\n\nIn the speech I made, I wanted to emphasize that in the DRC, although child mortality trends are optimistic according the MICS 2010 survey results, child mortality in Maniema remains the highest in the country and malaria is still a major cause of death in children under five.\n\nAccording to the pre-campaign survey conducted in Maniema in 2013, the prevalence of malaria in children under five is 76%; 60.7% of deaths in children under five are attributed to malaria. Of households in Maniema, 48% have at least one LLIN compared with 84.7% in 2010. In 2013, 49.4% of children under five had slept under a LLIN the previous night compared with 57.3% in 2010. Among pregnant women, 48.8% slept under a LLIN every night compared with 66.6% in 2010.\n\nThese indicators have deteriorated since the last distribution in Maniema. It became imperative to ensure the replacement of nets previously distributed in 2009 and 2010 as anti-malaria nets have a lifespan of about three years.\n\nThe campaign aims to protect at least 80% of households against malaria, offering Congolese children in Maniema a chance to grow up healthy.\n\nNETS FOR LIFE provides technical and logistical support for the “Hang Up” (distribution and hanging of nets) campaign in nine of the eighteen health zones making up the province.\n\n<strong>To learn more, find the logistics of this major operation below:</strong>\n\n<a href="/?p=3489">http://ponabana.com/defi-acheminer-1-250-000-moustiquaires-dans-la-province-du-maniema/</a>\n\nPhoto credit : UNICEF Germany/2013/Diana Mrazikova\n\n<strong>See photos of the campaign launch :</strong>\n\n[gallery type="slideshow" ids="3482,3481,3480,3479,3478,3477,3476,3475,3474,3473,3472,3471,3470,3469"]', 'The Fight Against Malaria is Growing in Maniema', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-fight-against-malaria-is-growing-in-maniema', '', '', '2014-01-17 13:24:56', '2014-01-17 13:24:56', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3927', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3919, 1, '2014-01-17 11:51:40', '2014-01-17 11:51:40', '<strong>More than 1000km of track, 300 km of river, the 1.25 million mosquito nets soaked with long-lasting insecticide that will be distributed in the Maniema province in January have gone on a long journey. A large-scale campaign that aims to curb the prevalence of malaria in this particularly affected region.</strong>\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Honore-Yao1.jpg"><img class="alignright" alt="Honore Yao" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Honore-Yao1.jpg" width="109" height="141" /></a>\n\n<strong>How to deliver such a quantity of mosquito nets in a distant and unstable region?</strong>\n\n<strong>Honoré Yao, our specialist consultant in logistics gives us some advice.</strong>\n\n<em><strong>What was your role in the delivery of these mosquito nets soaked with long-lasting insecticide?</strong></em>\n\nI have been sought for technical logistic support in the implementation of the campaign to distribute mosquito nets to all the households in the Maniema province. My objective was to contribute to the analysis and organization of an adequate logistic system.\n\n<em><strong>What volume represents 1.25 million mosquito nets?</strong></em>\n\nA total volume of 3750m<sup>3</sup> or a total weight of 845.5 tonnes.\n\n<em><strong>What means of transport have been used?</strong></em>\n\nFirst the trucks of course. Then, according to the location, the mosquito nets have been delivered by boat, bikes, carts and even by foot!\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik51.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-3508 alignright" alt="moustik5" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik51.jpg" width="247" height="185" /></a>\n\n<em><strong>What challenges have you been confronted with?</strong></em>\n\nI had to face two challenges: the infrastructure and transport problems and the constraint of storage. Two points were therefore essential: the mastery of the security and the ownership of the project by the political and administrative authorities.\n\nFor the 1<sup>st</sup> point, I met with the different persons in charge of the police and military units of Bunia, Kisangani and Kindu who gave some strict instructions to their colleagues working on the check-points along the 1075 km of track and 300 km of river in order to connect the Ugandan border to Kindu via Bunia and Kisangani. This open collaboration allowed me to have useful and regular pieces of information in order to best secure the 71 trailer trucks that delivered 1.25 million mosquito nets.\n\nThe large involvement of the local authorities was very useful. For example; a 30 day visa was granted to all the international drivers (previously 15), free parking for the trucks in the Bunia border police car park was suggested, and the Provincial Minister of Transport to the Office for roads helped us when the trucks were stuck in mud or had to cross the river on ferries.\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik101.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3516 aligncenter" alt="moustik10" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik101.jpg" width="339" height="163" /></a>\n\n<em><strong>What strategy have you put in place?</strong></em>\n\nI have put in place a centralized logistics because of the roads’ conditions and the large number of natural barriers. The stocks had to be received in one place before being redeployed to the area offices. This strategy enabled us to get a global vision and control of the whole campaign and therefore to secure the mosquito nets.\n\nThis system was preceded by the identification and evaluation of the storage sites, delivery systems and also of the local transporters who best know the sections.\n\nThe effectiveness of this campaign was made possible thanks to the large involvement of the heads of the UNICEF office in Bunia, Kisangani without forgetting the ownership of this project by the Head of UNICEF in Kundi. I have resolved the insufficient storage capacity by identifying secondary warehouses and directly restocking the health centers halfway between the main warehouses.\n\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik61.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3509 alignright" alt="moustik6" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/moustik61.jpg" width="297" height="188" /></a>\n\n<em><strong>Is this the first time that this strategy is being used?</strong></em>\n\nNo, this strategy of centralized logistics had already been tested out in 2012 at the time of the MILD campaign in the Bandundu province.\n\n<em><strong>Would you describe this campaign as a success?</strong></em>\n\nAccording to the logistic plan, everything has gone very well. No loss in terms of mosquito nets has been observed during the course of the campaign operations.\n\n<strong>Find the article on the importance of this campaign to Maniema in the fight against malaria:</strong>\n\n<a href="/?p=3463">http://ponabana.com/la-lutte-contre-le-paludisme-sintensifie-au-maniema/</a>', 'Challenge: Deliver 1.25 million mosquito nets in the Maniema province', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'challenge-deliver-1-25-million-mosquito-nets-in-the-maniema-province', '', '', '2014-01-17 11:51:40', '2014-01-17 11:51:40', '', 0, 'http://ponabana.com/?p=3919', 0, 'post', '', 0);
