(5184, 2, '2014-02-16 16:24:05', '2014-02-16 16:24:05', '<blockquote>\r\n<blockquote><b>UNICEF, in support of the Congolese government, is giving young people in the DRC a platform to defend children’s rights and become active in the decision-making processes that concern them.</b></blockquote>\r\n[accordion]\r\n\r\n[section title="CHILDREN''S RIGHTS"]<a href="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/IMG_0240.jpg"><img alt="IMG_0240" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/IMG_0240-1024x682.jpg" width="625" height="416" /></a>\r\n\r\nDespite the fact that the promotion of children’s rights has been a central element of the national agenda in recent years, the participation of children has often been merely symbolic. Given these observations, UNICEF and the DRC’s Ministry of Gender, Family Affairs and Children decided to give children a platform and the tools they need to defend their opinions and rights.\r\n\r\n[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="<strong>CHILDREN FROM 12 TO 17 YEARS OLD FROM ALL SOCIAL BACKGROUNDS</strong>"]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft" alt="IMG_0404" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/IMG_0404-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200" />\r\n\r\nAged from 12 to 17, the "Young Reporters" are girls and boys from all social backgrounds who come from organizations working for the protection, education, health and participation of children in the DRC.\r\n\r\nThe "Young Reporters" are trained to be more aware of their rights and better prepared to give their views on the problems that they encounter. They are introduced to the Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC) and practical workshops and games are organized to help them to understand all the issues related to children’s rights.\r\n\r\nThe children are trained to understand and master basic journalistic techniques. They are taught to master advocacy tools - videos, photos, public games and writing articles. Courses are delivered by a network of journalists and members of the UNICEF DRC team.\r\n\r\n[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="<strong>DEFEND YOUR RIGHTS AND EXPRESS YOUR OPINION</strong>"]\r\n\r\nThe "Young Reporters" program offers participants the opportunity to defend their rights by creating an environment that allows them to express their concerns, ideas, and recommendations to policy makers and managers at all levels. The importance given to their opinion in turn enhances dignity, justice, fairness and equality by placing the interests of children at the heart of the citizenship agenda.\r\n<div><dl id=""><dt><a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/2911.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" alt="29" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/2911.jpg" width="382" height="262" /></a></dt><dd>Les enfants reporters de Goma</dd></dl></div>\r\n[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="<strong>500 YOUTH REPORTERS TRAINED IN DRC''s 11 PROVINCES</strong>"]\r\n\r\nUNICEF has worked in partnership with the DRC’s Ministry of Gender, Family Affairs and Children so that the program can be implemented in 11 provinces.\r\n\r\nSince 2007, nearly 500 children have participated in the program and received basic training in audiovisual production and advocacy techniques to defend the rights of the child.\r\n\r\nSome discover a vocation for journalism, humanitarian work or law. The new skills and open-mindedness that this program offers children provide them with greater insight into their country, it''s problems and the solutions that can be found.\r\n\r\nWhen asked, most children recognise that now they know their rights, it is their responsibility to respect those of their own children and the children they meet throughout their lives.\r\n\r\nThe whole point of this program is to enable children to find the solutions to their own problems. They are often excluded from decisions that concern them when it seems obvious that they must be involved in building a more just society that is more respectful of its children.\r\n\r\n[/section]\r\n\r\n[section title="<strong>A TV SHOW, VIDEOS AND ARTICLES FOR CONCRETE RESULTS</strong>"]\r\n\r\n<img class="alignright" alt="IMG_0795" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/IMG_0795-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200" />\r\n\r\nFollowing a plea by young reporters in Kinshasa, the national television network RTNC has agreed to create a TV show called "The Voice of the Child".\r\n\r\nIn 2008, the Goma “Young Reporters” produced a series of videos called "Inside Witnesses" on the lives of displaced people in North Kivu. The videos were released internationally by the French newspaper <i>Le Monde</i> and prompted international and national debates.\r\n\r\nIn 2009, Young Reporters from Matadi found that in special schools for deaf and dumb children, parents had to pay teachers'' salaries. Based on the right of children to receive free and quality education, Young Reporters managed with their plea to the Governor to have the teachers’ salaries included in the 2010 budget.\r\n\r\nIn October 2012, the Francophone Summit was held in Kinshasa. On this occasion, Young Reporters were able to speak with several members of the DRC Parliament whom they alerted about the non-observance of children''s rights in their country. They also organised games about advocacy to inform other children about their rights.\r\n\r\nOne young reporter, Eunice, was invited to the African Union Summit in Addis Ababa where she represented children in Central Africa before African leaders. On this occasion she wrote a remarkable speech called "We, African Children" in which she recalled the right of the child to survival, freedom of expression, education and health, and called for a strategy to prevent armed conflict affecting children.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter" alt="IMG_0420" src="http://ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/IMG_0420-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200" />\r\n\r\n[/section]\r\n\r\n[/accordion]</blockquote>', 'Youth Reporters', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3546-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:24:05', '2014-02-16 16:24:05', '', 3546, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5184', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5182, 2, '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/3401.jpg"><img alt="340" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/3401.jpg" width="615" height="440" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>In the WASH sector, Unicef and its partner obtained the following results:</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">1. Increased government capacity and development of national strategies towards improving rural water, sanitation and hygiene throughout 11 provinces and 250 health zones of DRC.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">2. The national “Healthy Village and Healthy School” programme follows a community-driven demand-led strategy which gives families the opportunity to make informed choices while strengthening their resilience.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">3. At the end of June 2013 the VEA programme was operational in 11 Provinces, 212 Health Zones, and 5289 villages, of which 3256 were certified “Healthy Villages” and 1425 schools, of which 1054 were certified “Healthy Schools”. These results translate into the concrete results of 2,273,198 new persons gaining access to a healthy environment by surpassing minimum water, sanitation and hygiene targets.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">4. UNICEF WASH emergency programme assisted more than 800 000 persons in cholera-prone zones with preventive as well as WASH cholera-response packages (MYR Sitrep 2013). With the support of RRMP (Reponse Rapide aux Mouvements de Population, UNICEF DRC’s major emergency programme), 295,144 people were given access to water, sanitation and hygiene in emergency from January to Octobre 2013.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">5. In 2013, as UNICEF cluster lead agency for emergency WASH interventions, the WASH Cluster, with their members, coordinated the response to assist more than 4.5 million persons (MYR Sitrep 2013) to get access the WASH packages in order to save life, reduce vulnerability and meet the basic needs.</p>', 'Water and Sanition - Major achievements in DRC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3372-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '2014-02-16 16:23:13', '', 3372, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5182', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5185, 2, '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/131.jpg"><img alt="Girl smiling - the flower she wears on her forehead is for the International Women Day; at Kakoy Primary School, in Kakoy." src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/131.jpg" width="630" height="420" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>SCHOOL COSTS ARE TOO HIGH</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In 2010 a policy of school fee abolition was announced by the President yet its impact is limited Parents continue to bear the main burden of direct and indirect cost, including the running costs of schools and the incentives for teachers who are not on the official payroll or who are paid late. . UNICEF is assisting in the formative evaluation of this policy with a view to guiding policy re-orientations.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>EDUCATION IN THE NATIONAL BUDGET</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Over 2008-2010, the budget of the education sector accounted for about 3% of GDP and only 8.5% of the national budget. Although the education’s share of the national budget has increased to 13% in 2013, most domestic funding goes to pay salaries (see Interim Education Plan 2012/2016)  The body of teachers represents 80% of the size of the education public sector, while funding for other items such as operations and investments remain weak and often ineffective. There is an estimated gap of $270 million that is yet to be funded by the Government’s Interim Education Plan.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>QUALITY AND INVESTMENTS</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Children lack basic competencies and the more a student progresses on the educational ladder, the lower the retention rates. Major quality concerns include the lack of investments in initial teacher training, and incentives to attract good quality persons into the teaching profession. The curriculum is over-loaded with content that is irrelevant for 21<sup>st</sup> century needs , especially in terms of employable economic, social and emotional skills . UNICEF and partners are working toegther to support improvement of reading literacy, numeracy and life skills as core foundational skills. UNICEF is also supporting a new Peace Building in Education Programme which will strengthen the resilience of children, their parents and institutions to prevent, manage, and deal with conflicts and violence in and around schools.</p>', 'Education - Key Challenges in DRC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3536-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '2014-02-16 16:25:09', '', 3536, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5185', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5186, 2, '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/161.jpg"><img alt="16" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/161.jpg" width="773" height="515" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> </b>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223"><b>Indicateurs</b><b></b></td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258"><b>Données</b></td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190"><b>Année/Source</b><b></b></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Preschool enrollment rate 3.6%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">3,6%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Net Intake Rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=59%  G=52,9% T=56%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Gross enrollment rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=99,6% G=85,8% T=92,7%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Completion rate</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">B=68,5% G=49,1% T=58,8%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Parity Index</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">0,86</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Children (5-17 years) out of  school</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">7.4 millions (52% filles) ; 60% ont 6 et 7 ans</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Out of school Study 2012</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Transition from primary to secondary</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">74.7% (Gross rate)</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="223">Gross enrollment  rate in secondary school</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="258">38,5%</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="190">Statistical Yearbook 2010-2011</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Despite decades of economic and political crisis the coverage and performance of the education sector has increased in recent years. Although there is gender parity in enrolment at at primary level, important differences between provinces remain.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>EDUCATION COSTS ARE TOO HIGH</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Primary school completion rate has reached 58,8% in 2011. In spite of the fee free primary education policy,  education costs remains high for families. Government transfers to support the functionning of schools and administrative offices remains insufficient. Pupils are  requested to pay different types of fees including teachers’ salaries.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">After Nigeria and Ethiopia,  DRC has the largest number of school-children in sub-Saharan Africa. The 2012 Out of School study shows a direct relationship between the enrolment of children in school and the income status of a household. In poor families the access and retention of children is low, especially in rural areas, gender parity is 0.86 – and of those who reach university level, girls constitute only 30%</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EAD-2012-Enfants-en-dehors-de-lEcole-par-province-en-RDC1.jpg"><img alt="EAD 2012 Enfants en dehors de l''Ecole par province en RDC" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EAD-2012-Enfants-en-dehors-de-lEcole-par-province-en-RDC1.jpg" width="960" height="720" /></a>', 'Education - Key Statistics', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3531-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '2014-02-16 16:25:32', '', 3531, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5186', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5187, 2, '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '<img alt="15" src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/151.jpg" width="718" height="478" />\r\n\r\n<strong>IMPROVEMENT OF THE EDUCATION QUALITY</strong>\r\n\r\nOver the past four years (2008-2012), UNICEF has contributed over $ 80 million U.S. dollars to increase access and improve the quality of education for  more than 4 million children. During the 2012-2013 school-year UNICEF has invested more than 1.7 million dollars in school kits for 623,466 students and 14,922 teachers in the South and the West of the country.\r\n\r\n<strong>EDUCATION IN EMERGENCIES</strong>\r\n\r\nIn the conflict-affected East, direct cash transfer of funds to schools was done for a total of $ 650,000 in favor of school kits for 346.773 students and 7,677 teachers. To promote education in emergency and transition situations UNICEF trained teachers and parents on learner-centred methodologies in core curricula areas and psychosocial support for children affected by the conflict, thereby contributing to improved learner performance.\r\n\r\nAmong the 2.4 million internally displaced persons (IDP), half are children and 690,000 are old enough to attend primary school. The enrollment rate of children in IDP camps is around 37% (Sources: OCHA IDP Factsheet, July 2012). However, enrolment rates in the provinces affected by conflict compare favourably with non-emergency provinces thanks to emergency education support provided by various donors.\r\n\r\n<strong>ENHANCED PARTNERSHIPS</strong>\r\n\r\nAt policy level, UNICEF has contributed to improve knowledge on equity issues in education and the elaboration of policies and strategies to combat exclusion in education. UNICEF has also been instrumental in improvements in sector coordination among all partners as well as the development of a policy dialogue agenda to accompany sector reform. Sector analysis is currently ongoing with UNICEF support, which for the first time will produce a conflict-sensitive analysis to be used in the elaboration of the new education sector plan.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Education - Major achievements in DRC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3541-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '2014-02-16 16:25:46', '', 3541, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5187', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(5188, 2, '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '<a href="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/141.jpg"><img alt="Pupils on their way to school; at Plateau neighborhood, in Kikwit." src="http://staging.ponabana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/141.jpg" width="645" height="430" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>"REDUCING THE NUMBER OF CHILDREN OUT OF SCHOOL"</strong>\r\n<div style="text-align: justify;">\r\n\r\nFollowing the Education First High level meeting, a number of partners have pledged to support the acceleration of primary education in DRC. Within the framework of the Interim Education Plan, the recently approved GPE funding ($ 100 millions), complemented by other external resources (including UNICEF’s , DFID AFD, World Bank, USAID, Educate and Child/Qatar) will contribute a number of measures to fill existing financing gaps. UNICEF and DFID are supporting the elaboration of the Equity in Education policy and strategy to reduce the number of children out of school. AFD will support recurrent costs (especially teachers’ salaries, construction and rehabilitation of schools as well as quality education); USAID will also contribute to the Education First Initiative, focusing on Equitable Access and Quality.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nImportant steps to take include an increase of budget allocations for the education sector, increased investments in access and quality, especially dealing with the systemic challenges affecting teachers. . A budget monitoring and an accountability systemneed strengthening, including through promotion of local community participation in policy dialogue. . The capacity of all stakeholders in relation to financial and program management must be enhanced. The Information System for Management Education (EMIS) needs to be strengthened and government investments made to sustain routine collection and analysis of data. . UNICEF is currently supporting EMIS capacity strengthening at decentralized levels.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Education - The way forward in DRC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3525-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '2014-02-16 16:26:11', '', 3525, 'http://staging.ponabana.com/?p=5188', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
